style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Note\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1960 ||''[[Play of the Week]]'' ||Dolly Talbo || Episode: \"The Glass Harp\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Unforgiven (1960 film)|The Unforgiven]]''|| Mattilda Zachary ||\n|-\n|1962 || ''[[The Defenders (1961 TV series)|The Defenders]]''||Laura Clarendon || Episode: \"Grandma TNT\"\n|-\n| rowspan=2|1963 || ''[[Mr. Novak]]'' || Miss Maude Phipps || Episode: \"Hello, Miss Phipps\"\n|-\n|''[[Breaking Point (1963 TV series)|Breaking Point]]'' || Stella Manville || Episode: The Gnu, Now Almost Extinct\"\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1964 || ''[[The Defenders (1961 TV series)|The Defenders]]''||Mrs. Cooper || Episode: \"Stowaway\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Alfred Hitchcock Hour]]''  ||Bessie Carnby || Episode: \"Body in the Barn\"\n|-\n|1966 || ''[[Follow Me, Boys!]]'' || Hetty Seibert||\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1967 || ''[[Warning Shot (1967 film)|Warning Shot]]''||Alice Willows ||\n|-\n| ''[[The Comedians (1967 film)|The Comedians]]'' ||Mrs. Smith ||\n|-\n|1969 || ''Arsenic and Old Lace'' ||Martha Brewster ||TV movie  \n|}\n\n===1970s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Note\n|-\n|1976 || ''Twin Detectives'' ||Billy Jo Haskins || TV movie\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1978 || ''Sparrow'' || Widow||TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[A Wedding]]'' ||Nettie Sloan ||\n|}\n\n===1980s===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Year\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Title\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Role\n!style=\"background:#B0C4DE;\" | Note\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1981 ||''[[The Love Boat]]''||Mrs. Williams || Episode: \"The Successor\" \n|-\n| ''Thin Ice'' || Grandmother ||TV movie\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1983 || ''Hobson's Choice'' ||Miss Molly Winkle ||TV movie\n|-\n| ''[[Hambone and Hillie]]'' ||Hillie Radcliffe ||\n|-\n|1985 || ''[[American Playhouse]]'' ||Mrs. Loftus || Episode: \"Adventures of Huckleberry Finn\"\n|-\n|1986 || ''[[Sweet Liberty]]'' || Cecelia Burgess ||\n|-\n|1987 || ''[[The Whales of August]]'' || Sarah Webber || Final film role\n|}\n\n==References==\n* {{IMDb name|id=0001273|name=Lillian Gish}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140715083710/http://www.lilliangish.com/about/films1y.html Lilian Gish official website]\n\n[[Category:Actress filmographies|Gish, Lillian]]\n[[Category:Lillian Gish|Filmography]]\n", "name_user": "Moe1810", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e1960s", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lillian_Gish_filmography"}
{"title_page": "Ryesgade", "text_new": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = Ryesgade\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Ryesgade 2.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = \n| former_names    = \n| length_m        = 1360\n| width           =\n| location        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| quarter                 = [[N\u00f8rrebro]], [[\u00d8sterbro]]\n| postal_code     = 2100, 2200\n| metro                   = [[Trianglen Station|Trianglen]] \n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|41|31.38|N|12|34|1.14|E}}\n| direction_a             = Southwest\n| terminus_a              = [[Ravnsborggade]]\n| direction_b             = Northeast\n| terminus_b              = [[\u00d8sterbrogade]]\n| junction                = [[Fredensgade]]\n}}\n{{for|the street of Ryesgade in Aarhus|Ryesgade, Aarhus}}\n'''Ryesgade''' is a street straddling  the border of the [[N\u00f8rrebro]] and [[\u00d8sterbro]] districts of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. Together with Ravnsborggade, its continuation to the south, it forms the backbone of a small neighbourhood bounded by [[The Lakes, Copenhagen|The Lakes]] to the east, Blegdamsvej to the west, [[N\u00f8rrebrogade]] to the south and [[\u00d8sterbrogade]] to the north. The busy artery Fredensgade and the adjacent Fredens Park, effectively separates the N\u00f8rrebro and \u00d8sterbro portions of Ryesgade from each other. Ryesgade was formerly known for its many second-hand stores of which a few still exist today.\n\n==History==\n===Planning and street names===\n{{Wide image|Ryesgade (1860).jpg|800px|An 1860 rendering of the planned street}}\n\nThe area between Sortedam Lake and Blegdamsvej was formerly the site of a row of narrow lots with bleaching pongs. The plans for the new street was first presented in around 1860 as part of the plans for redevelopment of the area. It served the dual purpose of dividing the long lots in two and in the same time to facilitate the construction of a new main sewer along the lakes.\n\nThe street and its side streets were named for military figures from Denmark's most recent wars, [[First Schleswig War]] (1949&ndash;50) and [[Second Schleswig War]]  (1864). Ryesgade takes its name after [[Olaf Rye]]. The side streets are named after Hans Hedemann (Hedemannsgade), Hans Hedemann (Helgesensgade), Niels Christian Lunding (Lundingsgade), Johan Trepka  (Trepkasgade), Johan Irminger  (Irmingersgade),Christoph von Krogh (Kroghsgade(,Frederik L\u00e6ss\u00f8e (L\u00e6ss\u00f8esgade) and Frederik Adolph Schleppegrell (Schleppegrellsgade).\n\n===Early development, 1860-1900===\n[[File:Ryesgade set fra N\u00f8rrebro med Huset, der skal nedbrydes for Gadens udvidelse.png|thumb|The southern cul-de-sac seen from N\u00f8rrebrogade on a drawing by Lydvig Both, 1994]]\nThe street was constructed in stages with its last section, around Irmingersgade, not being constructed until the 1880s. For many years it was therefore made up of two dead end sections, accessed from the south and north respectively.\n\n[[File:Bryggeriet Ravnsborg.jpg|thumb|left|Ravnsborg Brewery]]\nThe first development along the street was a mixture of industrial and residential buildings. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aok.dk/teater/gasvaerket|title=Gasv\u00e6rket|publisher=AOK|accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref> Harald Drewsen designed a villa for [[Andreas Aagesen]] at No. 46. [[Benny Goldschmidt|Goldschmidt & Nordholm]]'s textile dyeing plant was located at No. 23. Ravnsborg Brewery (No. 27) was established in 1867 by the brewers F. C. Madsen and J. Vestberg. N\u00f8rrebros Iisv\u00e6rk, an industrial producer of ice, was located at No. 50. [[Camillus Nyrop]]'s  factory (No. 105) producedmedical instruments. Schulstad & Ludvigsen operated an industrial bakery in the street. [[NKT A/S|Nordiske Kabel- og Traadfabrikker]] opened at No. 105 in 1893 but moved to La Cours Cej in [[Frederiksberg]] in 1906.\n\nThe entertainment venue Sortedamslund was also located in the street.\n\n===20th century===\nOn 1 June 1983 squatters moved into No. 58.  No. 63&ndash;65 was also squatted on 4 December 1985 and cleared by the police on 11 February 1986. The situation culminated in the [[Battle of Ryesgade|Ryesgade Riots]] which occurred in mid-September. The squatters ultimately left No. 58 on 22 September.\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\n===Ravnsborggade to Fredensgade===\n[[Image:Nordisk Metalvarefabrik.JPG|thumb|No. 3: The former metal goods factory ]] \nA number of the old industrial buildings are still found in the N\u00f8rrebro section of the street. No. 3 is a former metal goods factory, Nordisk Metalvarefabrik. The main wing on Ryesgade was originally a social institution, built in 1852 to a design by [[Niels Sigfred Nebelong]]. The wing on Sankt Hans Gade and a number of smaller stable and storage buildings were added in 1971. In 1895 the complex was taken over by the metal goods factory which remained on the site until the 1940s. The building is now owned by C. W. Obel and houses creative businesses as well as [[N\u00f8rrebro Bryghus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwobel-ejendomme.dk/ejendomme/koebenhavn/ryesgade-3-koebenhavn.aspx?c=alle&p=7|title=Ryesgade|language=Danish|publisher=C.W. Obel|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref> No. 48 is a former starch factory. No. 51&ndash;55 is a former machine factory, Nielsen & Winther, built in 1916 to a design by Frederik Wagner.\n\nNo. 15-17 are the last surviving buildings of Sankt Johannes Stiftelse. It was built in around 1885 and served as a combination of a hospital, workhouse and orphanage. It was later merged with Almindelig Hospital under the name N\u00f8rre Hospital. Most of the buildings have been demolished and replaced by the senior citizens home S\u00f8lund on the other side of the street.\n\nGoldschmidts stiftelse (No. 31) was built by [[Benny Goldschmidt]] to provide affordable housing for dyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starbas.net/arkivskaber.php?id=2632&laes_mere=ja|title=Grosserer B. Goldschmidts og hustrus stiftelse|language=Danish|publisher=K\u00f8benhavns Kommune|accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Fredensgade to \u00d8sterbrogade===\n[[Image:Ryesgades Skole.JPG|thumb|left|The former Ryesgade School ]] \nSortedam School is located at No. 120. No. 101 is the former Ryesgade School, which was completed in 1891 to a design by [[Hans J\u00f8rgen Holm]] . On the opposite side of the street, at No. 104, is the rear side of Soldenfeldts Stiftelse, a home for elderly women. The front of the building faces Sortedams Doseringen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soldenfeldt.dk/huset.html|title=Huset|language=Danish|publisher=Soldenfeldts Stiftelse|accessdate=2013-09-12}}</ref> \n\n[[Image:Nazaret Kirke Copenhagen 3.jpg|thumb|150px|Nazareth Church ]] \nThere are two churches in the street. Church of Peace was built in 1899, although the tower was not added until 1906. [[Nazareth Church, Copenhagen|Nazareth Church]] at No. 106B was built between 102 and 104 to a design by Victor Nyeb\u00f8lle. In 2013, Church of Peace was one of 14 churches in Copenhagen which was nominated for closure by the [[Diocese of Copenhagen|Bishop of Copenhagen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politiken.dk/indland/ECE1889758/fakta-disse-14-kirker-skal-lukkes/|title=Fakta: Disse 14 kirker skal lukkes|language=Danish|publisher=Politiken|accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref>\n\nFotografernes Stiftelse (No. 100) was built by the Danish Association of Photographers to provide affordable housing for indigent photographers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fotohistorie.com/hauerslev-johannes-kbh-n.html|title=Johannes Hauerslev, F\u00e6lledvej 9, Kj\u00f8benhavn. 1860\u20131921. Fotograf 1887\u20131918.|language=Danish|website=fotohistorie.comk|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Memorial plaque==\nOn the corner of Irmingergade, there is a plaque commemorating Svend Rothenberg Frederiksen, a member of the [[Danish resistance movement]], who was shot at the site on 2 May 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bibliotek.kk.dk/raadhusbibliotekets-online-resurser/mindetavler-koebenhavn/oesterbro|title=Mindetavler p\u00e5 \u00d8sterbro|language=Danish|publisher=biblioteket.dk|accessdate=2013-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe street is used as a location in the 1971 film ''[[The Missing Clerk]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://danskefilm.dk/lokation.php?id=1539|title=Ryesgade, K\u00f8benhavnK\u00f8benhavn|language=Danish|website=danskefilm.dk|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ravnsborggade]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ryesgade, Copenhagen}}\n* [https://www.dengang.dk/artikler/2101 Source]\n\n{{\u00d8sterbro}}\n\n{{coord|55.6921|N|12.5670|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in N\u00f8rrebro]]\n[[Category:Streets in \u00d8sterbro]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox street\n| name            = Ryesgade\n| native_name     = \n| image           = Ryesgade 2.jpg\n| image_size      = 320px\n| caption         = \n| former_names    = \n| length_m        = 1360\n| width           =\n| location        = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]\n| quarter                 = [[N\u00f8rrebro]], [[\u00d8sterbro]]\n| postal_code     = 2100, 2200\n| metro                   = [[Trianglen Station|Trianglen]] \n| coordinates     = {{coord|55|41|31.38|N|12|34|1.14|E}}\n| direction_a             = Southwest\n| terminus_a              = [[Ravnsborggade]]\n| direction_b             = Northeast\n| terminus_b              = [[\u00d8sterbrogade]]\n| junction                = [[Fredensgade]]\n}}\n{{for|the street of Ryesgade in Aarhus|Ryesgade, Aarhus}}\n'''Ryesgade''' is a street straddling  the border of the [[N\u00f8rrebro]] and [[\u00d8sterbro]] districts of [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. Together with Ravnsborggade, its continuation to the south, it forms the backbone of a small neighbourhood bounded by [[The Lakes, Copenhagen|The Lakes]] to the east, Blegdamsvej to the west, [[N\u00f8rrebrogade]] to the south and [[\u00d8sterbrogade]] to the north. The busy artery Fredensgade and the adjacent Fredens Park, effectively separates the N\u00f8rrebro and \u00d8sterbro portions of Ryesgade from each other. Ryesgade was formerly known for its many second-hand stores of which a few still exist today.\n\n==History==\n===Planning and street names===\n{{Wide image|Ryesgade (1860).jpg|800px|An 1860 rendering of the planned street}}\n\nThe area between Sortedam Lake and Blegdamsvej was formerly the site of a row of narrow lots with bleaching pongs. The plans for the new street was first presented in around 1860 as part of the plans for redevelopment of the area. It served the dual purpose of dividing the long lots in two and in the same time to facilitate the construction of a new main sewer along the lakes.\n\nThe street and its side streets were named for military figures from Denmark's most recent wars, [[First Schleswig War]] (1949&ndash;50) and [[Second Schleswig War]]  (1864). Ryesgade takes its name after [[Olaf Rye]]. The side streets are named after Hans Hedemann (Hedemannsgade), Hans Hedemann (Helgesensgade), Niels Christian Lunding (Lundingsgade), Johan Trepka  (Trepkasgade), Johan Irminger  (Irmingersgade),Christoph von Krogh (Kroghsgade(,Frederik L\u00e6ss\u00f8e (L\u00e6ss\u00f8esgade) and Frederik Adolph Schleppegrell (Schleppegrellsgade).\n\n===Early development, 1860-1900===\n[[File:Ryesgade set fra N\u00f8rrebro med Huset, der skal nedbrydes for Gadens udvidelse.png|thumb|The southern cul-de-sac seen from N\u00f8rrebrogade on a drawing by Lydvig Both, 1994]]\nThe street was constructed in stages with its last section, around Irmingersgade, not being constructed until the 1880s. For many years it was therefore made up of two dead end sections, accessed from the south and north respectively.\n\n[[File:Bryggeriet Ravnsborg.jpg|thumb|left|Ravnsborg Brewery]]\nThe first development along the street was a mixture of industrial and residential buildings. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aok.dk/teater/gasvaerket|title=Gasv\u00e6rket|publisher=AOK|accessdate=2010-01-04}}</ref> Harald Drewsen designed a villa for [[Andreas Aagesen]] at No. 46. [[Benny Goldschmidt|Goldschmidt & Nordholm]]'s textile dyeing plant was located at No. 23. Ravnsborg Brewery (No. 27) was established in 1867 by the brewers F. C. Madsen and J. Vestberg. N\u00f8rrebros Iisv\u00e6rk, an industrial producer of ice, was located at No. 50. [[Camillus Nyrop]]'s  factory (No. 105) producedmedical instruments. Schulstad & Ludvigsen operated an industrial bakery in the street. [[NKT A/S|Nordiske Kabel- og Traadfabrikker]] opened at No. 105 in 1893 but moved to La Cours Cej in [[Frederiksberg]] in 1906.\n\nThe entertainment venue Sortedamslund was also located in the street.\n\n===20th century===\nOn 1 June 1983 squatters moved into No. 58.  No. 63&ndash;65 was also squatted on 4 December 1985 and cleared by the police on 11 February 1986. The situation culminated in the [[Battle of Ryesgade|Ryesgade Riots]] which occurred in mid-September. The squatters ultimately left No. 58 on 22 September.\n\n==Notable buildings and residents==\n===Ravnsborggade to Fredensgade===\n[[Image:Nordisk Metalvarefabrik.JPG|thumb|No. 3: The former metal goods factory ]] \nA number of the old industrial buildings are still found in the N\u00f8rrebro section of the street. No. 3 is a former metal goods factory, Nordisk Metalvarefabrik. The main wing on Ryesgade was originally a social institution, built in 1852 to a design by [[Niels Sigfred Nebelong]]. The wing on Sankt Hans Gade and a number of smaller stable and storage buildings were added in 1971. In 1895 the complex was taken over by the metal goods factory which remained on the site until the 1940s. The building is now owned by C. W. Obel and houses creative businesses as well as [[N\u00f8rrebro Bryghus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cwobel-ejendomme.dk/ejendomme/koebenhavn/ryesgade-3-koebenhavn.aspx?c=alle&p=7|title=Ryesgade|language=Danish|publisher=C.W. Obel|accessdate=2013-08-12}}</ref> No. 48 is a former starch factory. No. 51&ndash;55 is a former machine factory, Nielsen & Winther, built in 1916 to a design by Frederik Wagner.\n\nNo. 15-17 are the last surviving buildings of Sankt Johannes Stiftelse. It was built in around 1885 and served as a combination of a hospital, workhouse and orphanage. It was later merged with Almindelig Hispital under the name N\u00f8rre Hospital. Most of the buildings have been demolished and replaced by the senior citizens home S\u00f8lund on the other side of the street.\n\nGoldschmidts stiftelse (No. 31) was built by [[Benny Goldschmidt]] to provide affordable housing for dyers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.starbas.net/arkivskaber.php?id=2632&laes_mere=ja|title=Grosserer B. Goldschmidts og hustrus stiftelse|language=Danish|publisher=K\u00f8benhavns Kommune|accessdate=28 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Fredensgade to \u00d8sterbrogade===\n[[Image:Ryesgades Skole.JPG|thumb|left|The former Ryesgade School ]] \nSortedam School is located at No. 120. No. 101 is the former Ryesgade School, which was completed in 1891 to a design by [[Hans J\u00f8rgen Holm]] . On the opposite side of the street, at No. 104, is the rear side of Soldenfeldts Stiftelse, a home for elderly women. The front of the building faces Sortedams Doseringen.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soldenfeldt.dk/huset.html|title=Huset|language=Danish|publisher=Soldenfeldts Stiftelse|accessdate=2013-09-12}}</ref> \n\n[[Image:Nazaret Kirke Copenhagen 3.jpg|thumb|150px|Nazareth Church ]] \nThere are two churches in the street. Church of Peace was built in 1899, although the tower was not added until 1906. [[Nazareth Church, Copenhagen|Nazareth Church]] at No. 106B was built between 102 and 104 to a design by Victor Nyeb\u00f8lle. In 2013, Church of Peace was one of 14 churches in Copenhagen which was nominated for closure by the [[Diocese of Copenhagen|Bishop of Copenhagen]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politiken.dk/indland/ECE1889758/fakta-disse-14-kirker-skal-lukkes/|title=Fakta: Disse 14 kirker skal lukkes|language=Danish|publisher=Politiken|accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref>\n\nFotografernes Stiftelse (No. 100) was built by the Danish Association of Photographers to provide affordable housing for indigent photographers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fotohistorie.com/hauerslev-johannes-kbh-n.html|title=Johannes Hauerslev, F\u00e6lledvej 9, Kj\u00f8benhavn. 1860\u20131921. Fotograf 1887\u20131918.|language=Danish|website=fotohistorie.comk|accessdate=30 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Memorial plaque==\nOn the corner of Irmingergade, there is a plaque commemorating Svend Rothenberg Frederiksen, a member of the [[Danish resistance movement]], who was shot at the site on 2 May 1945.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://bibliotek.kk.dk/raadhusbibliotekets-online-resurser/mindetavler-koebenhavn/oesterbro|title=Mindetavler p\u00e5 \u00d8sterbro|language=Danish|publisher=biblioteket.dk|accessdate=2013-09-12}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nThe street is used as a location in the 1971 film ''[[The Missing Clerk]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://danskefilm.dk/lokation.php?id=1539|title=Ryesgade, K\u00f8benhavnK\u00f8benhavn|language=Danish|website=danskefilm.dk|accessdate=16 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ravnsborggade]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ryesgade, Copenhagen}}\n* [https://www.dengang.dk/artikler/2101 Source]\n\n{{\u00d8sterbro}}\n\n{{coord|55.6921|N|12.5670|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Streets in N\u00f8rrebro]]\n[[Category:Streets in \u00d8sterbro]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: hispital\u2192hospital", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ryesgade"}
{"title_page": "Atherton, Greater Manchester", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England     \n|official_name=            Atherton\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.523|-2.495|display=inline,title}}\n|population=               22,000\n|population_ref=<ref name=WiganCore>{{citation |title=Wigan Core Strategy 2013|publisher=Wigan Council|url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/Docs/PDF/Council/Strategies-Plans-and-Policies/Planning/Adopted-Core-Strategy.pdf|accessdate=12 February 2014|date=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n|metropolitan_borough=     [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan|Wigan]]\n|metropolitan_county=      [[Greater Manchester]]\n|region =                  North West England  \n|constituency_westminster= [[Bolton West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolton West]]        \n|constituency_westminster1= [[Leigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Leigh]]\n|post_town=                MANCHESTER\n|postcode_district =       M46  \n|postcode_area=            M  \n|dial_code=                01942\n|os_grid_reference=        SD672030\n|london_distance=          {{convert|171|mi|km|0|abbr=on}}&nbsp;[[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n|static_image_name=        Market Street, Atherton.jpg\n|static_image_caption=     Market Street\n}}\n\n'''Atherton''' (pop. 20,300) is a town in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]], in [[Greater Manchester]], England and [[Historic counties of England|historically]] was historically a part of [[Lancashire]]. The town,  including [[Hindsford]], [[Howe Bridge]] and [[Hag Fold railway station|Hag Fold]], is {{convert|5|mi|km|1}} east of [[Wigan]], {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} north of [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], and {{convert|10.7|mi|km|1}} northwest of [[Manchester]]. From the 17th century, for about 300 years, Atherton was known as Chowbent, which was frequently shortened to Bent, the town's old nickname.\n\nAtherton was associated with coal mining and nail manufacture from the 14th century, encouraged by outcropping coal seams. At the beginning of the 20th century the town was described as \"the centre of a district of collieries, cotton mills and iron-works, which cover the surface of the country with their inartistic buildings and surroundings, and are linked together by the equally unlovely dwellings of the people\".<ref name=vch/> Atherton's last deep coal mine closed in 1966, and the last working cotton mills closed in 1999. Today the town is the third largest retail centre in the Borough of Wigan; almost 20% of those employed in the area work in the wholesale and retail trades, although there is still some significant manufacturing industry in the town.\n\nEvidence has been discovered of a [[Roman Britain|Roman]] road passing through the area, on the ancient route between Coccium (Wigan) and [[Mamucium]] (Manchester). Following the [[Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain|Anglo-Saxon]] invasion of England, Atherton, which is built on and around seven brooks, became part of the manor of [[Warrington]] until the [[Norman conquest]], when it became a township or [[vill]] in the ancient parish of Leigh.<ref name=\"GENUKI Parish map\">{{citation |title=Atherton map|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Atherton/ParishMap.shtml |publisher=genuki.org.uk |accessdate=31 August 2009}}</ref> Since 1974 the town has been part of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, a local government district of the [[metropolitan county|Metropolitan County]] of [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Toponymy===\nAtherton was recorded as Aderton in 1212 and 1242, and Atherton in 1259.<ref name=vch>{{citation |last1= Farrer |first1=William |last2=Brownbill |first2= J. (editors) |title=Atherton |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41363 |work=A History of the County of Lancaster: Volume 3 |publisher=[[Victoria County History]] |pages=435\u2013439 |year=1907 |accessdate=28 August 2009}}</ref>\nOpinions differ as to the derivation of the name. One is the farmstead or village of a man named Aethelhere, an [[Old English]] personal name and the suffix ''tun'', meaning an enclosure, farmstead or manor estate;<ref>{{Harvnb|Mills|1998|p=10}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Mills|1998|p=406}}</ref> another is ''adre'', Saxon for little brook with the suffix ''tun''.<ref name=\"Lunn1971, p.1\">{{Harvnb|Lunn|1971|p=1}}</ref> Either is possible as Atherton is bounded by brooks to the west and south, and crossed by several others. The western boundary is [[Hindsford]] Brook, originally named Goderic Brook after a [[Saxon]] saint.<ref name=\"Lunn1971, p.2\">{{Harvnb|Lunn|1971|p=2}}</ref>\n\nThe Chow&nbsp;\u2013 recorded as Chew, Cholle and Chowl&nbsp;\u2013 family were tenants of the Athertons living at the valley by Chanters Brook. This part of the township became known as Chow's Bent but the meaning of Bent has been lost, perhaps a bend or slope. It was referred to in the 14th century as Chollebynt or Shollebent.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=15|ps=none}} Chowbent, or Bent, was the name given to the built-up part of Atherton from the mid-17th century for at least 300&nbsp;years.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=10|ps=none}}  As the population grew, the town was called Atherton, although the names ''Chowbent'' or ''Bent'' are used by locals.\n\n===Early history===\nEvidence of a Roman road and [[Bronze Age]] settlement have been found in the area.<ref name=\"WAS\">{{citation |title=Newsletter 66|url=http://www.wiganarchsoc.co.uk/content/News_Letters/news066.htm|publisher=wiganarchsoc.co.uk |accessdate=30 November 2009}}</ref> The Roman road between Manchester and Wigan is shown on the 1849 6\" [[Ordnance Survey|OS map]] crossing Miller's Lane at 90&nbsp;degrees about halfway down.<ref name=\"Wigan Archaeological Society\">{{citation |title=Newsletter 71|url=http://www.wiganarchsoc.co.uk/content/News_Letters/news071.htm|publisher=wiganarchsoc.co.uk |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> The site of Gadbury Brickworks at [[Gibfield Colliery]] has been excavated, and evidence of Roman and possibly earlier settlements found.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=2146411154|title=Dig unearths ancient settlement and Roman road |publisher=megalithic.co.uk |accessdate=10 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Manor===\n[[File:Joseph Wright - Mrs. Robert Gwillym.jpg|thumb|upright|Richard Atherton's daughter Elizabeth, Mrs Robert Gwillym, painted by [[Joseph Wright of Derby]]]]\nThe [[manorialism|manor]] was held by the Atherton family from the de Botelers, whose chief manor was at [[Warrington]].<ref name=vch/> William and Nicholas Atherton fought at the [[Battle of Agincourt]] in 1415.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=9|ps=none}} The manor house was situated towards the south of the ancient [[Township (England)|township]]. [[Christopher Saxton]]'s map shows a [[medieval deer park]] in the time of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]].<ref name=vch/><ref>{{citation |publisher= ancestry.com |title=Christopher Saxton's 1579 map |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~genmaps/genfiles/COU_files/ENG/LAN/saxton_lancs_1579.htm |accessdate=16 September 2009 }}</ref>  \"Mad\" Richard Atherton, the last direct male descendant of the Athertons is remembered for two events; his expulsion of the congregation from the first Atherton Chapel in 1721,{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=99|ps=none}} and building [[Atherton Hall, Leigh|Atherton Hall]] on a grand scale, to designs by architect William Wakefield. Work on the hall started in 1723 and was not finished until 1743.{{sfn|Pollard|Pevsner|Sharples|2006|p=140|ps=none}} The carriage drive from the hall led over Lion's Bridge down an avenue to gates which faced [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Leigh|the parish church in Leigh]] where the Athertons had a chapel.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=111|ps=none}} Richard Vernon Atherton was the last of the Atherton male line. He married Elizabeth Farington and had a daughter named Elizabeth.\n\nThe Atherton family's association with the township ended with Richard Atherton's death in 1726. His daughter, Elizabeth, married Robert Gwillym and their son, Robert Vernon Atherton, married Henrietta Maria Legh. They had five children; the sons died young, and their eldest daughter Henrietta Maria Atherton married Thomas Powys, 2nd Baron Lilford<ref>{{Harvnb|Lunn|1971|p=128}}</ref> whose father was ennobled by [[Pitt the Younger]] in 1797, taking the title of [[Baron Lilford]]. He left his estates to his son, [[Thomas Powys, 3rd Baron Lilford|Thomas Atherton Powys]]. The Atherton estate was inherited by Lord Lilford, who preferred to live at his family seat, [[Lilford Hall]] in Northamptonshire. Lord Lilford could not afford the upkeep of another house and Atherton Hall was put up for sale but, after failing to sell, it was demolished in 1824. Some outbuildings were left standing and are private property still known as Atherton Hall.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=160|ps=none}} This portion of Atherton was incorporated into [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]] in 1894 and the area became a public park.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=195|ps=none}}\n\n===Two battles===\nThe area was divided in its allegiance during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]]. In 1642, men of Chowbent were on their way to Leigh Church when word came that [[James Stanley, 7th Earl of Derby]]'s [[Cavalier|Royalist]] troops were marching through Leigh, probably en route for Manchester. The men of Chowbent armed themselves and drove the Earl's men back to Lowton Common, killing some, wounding others and taking prisoner about 200 men: \"...&nbsp;we are all upon our guard, and the Naylors of Chowbent, instead of making Nayles, have busied themselves making Bills and Battle Axes.\" (Civil War tracts of Lancashire, Chetham Society Series, vol II).{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=27|ps=none}}\n\nIn 1715, during the [[Jacobite rising of 1715|Jacobite rising]] the supporters of the [[Old Pretender]] were marching on [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]. General [[Charles Wills]] wrote to [[James Wood (minister)|Minister Wood]] of Atherton Chapel asking him to raise a force to be at [[Cuerden Green]] the following day, 12 November.<ref>{{Harvnb|Wright|1921|p=28}}</ref>  Minister Wood led a force of Chowbent men who were given the job of guarding the bridge over the [[River Ribble]] at [[Walton-le-Dale]] and a ford at [[Penwortham]], which they defended successfully. The Highlanders were routed, and for his efforts Parson James Wood was given a \u00a3100 [[Life annuity|annuity]] (equivalent to \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|100|1715|r=-2}}}} in {{Inflation-year|UK}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} by Parliament and the title \"The General\" by his congregation.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=31|ps=none}}\n\n===Industrial history===\nAtherton, along with neighbouring [[Shakerley]], was associated with coal mining and nail manufacture. Alexander Naylor was taxed on his goods in 1332, showing the industry was present for at least 600&nbsp;years. Encouraged by the proximity of outcrops of coal, iron was brought from Derbyshire, Yorkshire and Spain. Several types of nails were made, including [[lath]] nails, [[slate]] nails, thatching nails and sparrowbills. The nail smithies manufactured [[plough]]s and [[scythe]]s; their products were taken by [[pack horse]] to be sold in Manchester, [[Denbigh]], [[Clitheroe]] and [[Kendal]].{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=19|ps=none}} The nail industry developed into the manufacture of nuts and bolts. Thomas Blakemore was the first in 1843 and by 1853 there were eight manufacturers of nuts and bolts including James Prestwich and Robert Parker.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=171|ps=none}} Some nut and bolt manufacturers also made spindles and flyers for spinning machinery.<ref name=vch/> Collier Brook Bolt Works on Bag Lane dating from 1856 survives and is a Grade II listed building.<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068454 |desc=Collier Brook Bolt House|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\nCoal had been mined for several hundred years in numerous shallow shafts and [[adit]]s, but took on greater importance when in 1776 Robert Vernon Atherton leased the coal rights to Thomas Guest from Leigh and John Fletcher from [[Bolton]].{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=117|ps=none}} In 1845 the era of deep mining commenced with the sinking of Fletcher's Lover's Lane pit at [[Howe Bridge]]. The Crombouke Day-Eye, a drift mine accessing the shallow Brassy and [[Crombouke mine]]s, opened in 1870 and closed in 1907. (A coal seam was referred to as a \"mine\" in this part of Lancashire.) By the early 1870s [[Fletcher, Burrows and Company]]'s [[Howe Bridge Colliery]], the biggest of the three Howe Bridge pits, was sunk to the Black & White, or Seven Foot mine. The pit closed in 1959.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=187|ps=none}}{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=38|ps=none}} [[Gibfield Colliery]], situated alongside the [[Bolton and Leigh Railway]], was working in 1829, and coal was mined from the [[Trencherbone mine]].{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=33|ps=none}} Forty years later a {{convert|1169|ft|adj=on}} shaft was sunk to Arley Mine. The pit closed in 1963. In September 1913 the first pit head baths in the country were opened at Gibfield. [[Chanters Colliery]] was in [[Hindsford]], where {{convert|1120|ft|adj=on}} shafts were sunk to the Trencherbone mine in 1854.{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=328|ps=none}} In the late 1890s shafts were deepened to {{convert|1800|ft}} to reach the Arley mine. Atherton had its share of mining disasters \u2014 on 11 February 1850 five men died in a gas explosion caused by a lighted candle at Gibfield,<ref>{{citation|title=Gibfield Colliery Disaster |url=http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1850_54.pdf |format=PDF |page=1 |publisher=cmhrc.co.uk |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613010419/http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1850_54.pdf |archivedate=13 June 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> and 27 men died at Lovers Lane Colliery after a [[firedamp]] explosion caused by blown-out shot on 28 March 1872.<ref>{{citation |title=Lovers Lane Disaster Disaster|url=  http://www.dmm.org.uk/names/d1870-79.htm| publisher=dmm.org.uk |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref> On 6 March 1957 eight men died at Chanters Colliery after an explosion of gas.<ref>{{citation|title=Chanters Colliery Disaster |url=http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1952_57.pdf |page=14 |publisher=cmhrc.co.uk |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613010347/http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1952_57.pdf |archivedate=13 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> \nChanters closed in 1966 bringing the era of deep coal mining in the town to an end.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=205|ps=none}}\nIn 1908, the Lancashire and Cheshire Coal Owners Association opened [[Howe Bridge Mines Rescue Station]].<ref>{{citation |title=Howe Bridge Mines Rescue |url=http://www.colsal.org.uk/sites/lancashireminesrescue/HOWEBRIDGEMRS.asp |publisher=colsal.org.uk |accessdate=14 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:EnaMill.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Ena Mill in 2000]]\nThe [[cotton mill]]s grew out of a cottage spinning and weaving industry that was widespread across the district. As industrialisation gathered pace, local [[Weaver (occupation)|weavers]] felt threatened by the advent of powered [[loom]]s, and in April 1812 a mob smashed the machines and burnt down a new factory, [[Westhoughton Mill]], in neighbouring [[Westhoughton]]. For this, the [[Luddite]]s, three men and a boy of 14, were tried at [[Lancaster Castle|Lancaster Assizes]] and hanged.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=152|ps=none}} [[Fustian]] was woven and after 1827 silk<ref name=vch/> also was brought from Manchester.{{sfn|Holcroft|1998|p=10|ps=none}} In 1938 [[James Burton (millowner)|James Burton]] had built [[cotton mill]]s on both sides of the Hindsford Brook including Lodge Mill. Dan Lane Spinning and Doubling Mills were built in the 1840s and lasted until the 1950s. Howe Bridge Spinning Mills, the largest complex in Atherton was started in 1868 and the last mill built in 1919. It closed as a textile factory in early 1999.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=180|ps=none}}  Mills built in the 20th century were Laburnum Mills in 1905 (closed 1980), and Ena Mill in 1908 which closed in 1999. The Ena Mill, now converted for other uses, is a Grade II [[listed building]].{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=199|ps=none}}<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1253159 |desc=Ena Mill|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Atherton Town Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1548868.jpg|thumb|Atherton Town Hall]]\nAtherton is an electoral ward of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]. The ward elects three councillors to the 75-member metropolitan borough council, Wigan's [[local authority]]. As of 2019 Councillors in all three local wards are Independents.<ref name=ward>{{citation |title=Councillor & Committee Details |url=http://democracy.wigan.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx?bcr=1 |publisher=wigan.gov.uk|author=Wigan Metropolitan Borough Council|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> \nHistorically, Atherton was in the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|Hundred]] of [[West Derby (hundred)|West Derby]], a judicial division of southwest Lancashire. Atherton was one of the six townships or [[vill]]s that made up the ancient ecclesiastical parish of Leigh.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=1|ps=none}} The townships existed before the parish. The manor of Atherton was held by the Atherton family from the de Botelers, whose chief manor was at [[Warrington]].<ref name=vch/>\n\nUnder the terms of the [[Poor Law Amendment Act 1834]] the townships were part of the Leigh [[Poor Law Union]] which was established on 26 January 1837 comprising an area covering the whole of the ancient parish of Leigh and part of [[Winwick, Cheshire|Winwick]]. Workhouses existed in [[Pennington, Greater Manchester|Pennington]], [[Culcheth]], [[Tyldesley]], [[Lowton]] and Hag Fold in Atherton, but the [[Leigh Union workhouse]] at Atherleigh replaced them in the 1850s.<ref name=Workhouses>{{citation |title=Leigh |url= http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Leigh/|publisher=workhouses.org.uk |accessdate=31 August 2009}}</ref> In 1863 the Local Government Act 1858 was adopted for the township, meaning it was governed by a [[local board of health]], a type of regulatory body responsible for standards of hygiene and sanitation in the township. In 1894 part of the township was added to Leigh Urban District; the remainder became [[Atherton Urban District]]. The [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] was abolished in 1974 under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], when the area became part of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, a local government district of the [[metropolitan county]] of [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name=\"GM Gazetteer A\">{{citation |url=http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazza.htm |title=Greater Manchester Gazetteer |publisher=Greater Manchester County Record Office|accessdate=3 June 2010|archivedate=18 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718144214/http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazza.htm}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a review of parliamentary representation in Greater Manchester, Atherton is part of the [[Bolton West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolton West]] Parliamentary constituency. It is the only ward in the borough to be represented outside a Wigan borough seat (the remainder of the borough is represented by Leigh, Makerfield or Wigan).<ref name=\"About Bolton West\">{{citation|url=http://www.labouronline.org/wibs/165798/e10eff00-8855-3bf4-6d31-76d6329f2426|title=Bolton West |publisher=labouronline.org |accessdate=8 November 2009}}</ref> Atherton's MP is [[Chris Green (politician)|Chris Green]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] who won the parliamentary seat for Bolton West in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref name=\"Election 2015\">{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000580|title=Election 2015: Bolton West|accessdate=28 August 2016|work=BBC News}}</ref> Howe Bridge is in the [[Leigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Leigh]] constituency represented by [[James Grundy (politician)|James Grundy]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)]]).\n\n==Geography==\n{{Further|Geography of Greater Manchester}}\n{{climate chart|Atherton\n|1|6|70\n|1|7|50\n|3|9|60\n|4|12|50\n|7|15|60\n|10|18|70\n|12|20|70\n|12|20|80\n|10|17|70\n|8|14|80\n|4|9|80\n|2|7|80\n|float=right\n|source={{citation |url=http://weather.yahoo.com/climo/UKXX1090_f.html?woeid=11353 |year=2008 |title=Atherton Weather |accessdate=9 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608235905/http://weather.yahoo.com/climo/UKXX1090_f.html?woeid=11353 |archive-date=8 June 2011 |url-status = dead }}\n|clear=both\n}} \nAt {{coord|53|31|23|N|2|29|44|W|type:city}} (53.5231\u00b0, \u22122.4955\u00b0), and {{convert|171|mi|km|0}} northwest of [[central London]], Atherton is situated {{convert|5|mi}} east of Wigan and {{convert|10.7|mi}} west-northwest of the city of Manchester, at the eastern end of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan.\n\nAtherton, which includes Hindsford to the southeast, [[Howe Bridge]] in the southwest, and Hag Fold in the north, is generally low lying. The soil is clay in much of the township.<ref name=vch/> The southwest of the town is {{convert|100|ft}} above sea level, rising to {{convert|250|ft}} in the north.<ref name=vch/> Atherton is built around seven brooks: the Shakerley Brook forms the western boundary with Tyldesley; Chanters Brook flows through the area known as \"The Valley\"; Knight's Brook (Bag Lane); Colliers Brook; Small Brook is the boundary with [[Westleigh, Greater Manchester|Westleigh]]; Westhoughton Brook forms the boundary with Daisy Hill; and Red Waters Brook.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=2|ps=none}} The underlying rocks are the [[coal measures]] of the [[Manchester Coalfield]].\n\nAtherton's climate is generally temperate, like the rest of Greater Manchester. The mean highest and lowest temperatures ({{convert|13.2|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} and {{convert|6.4|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}) are slightly above the national average, while the annual rainfall ({{convert|806.6|mm|in}}) and average hours of sunshine (1394.5 hours) are respectively above and below the national averages.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/sites/manchester_airport.html |title=Manchester Airport 1971\u20132000 weather averages |publisher=[[Met Office]] |year=2001 |accessdate=9 November 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929103050/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/sites/manchester_airport.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |author=Met Office |title=Annual England weather averages |publisher=Met Office |year=2007 |accessdate=9 November 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024000/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe town is situated on the old high road, now the [[A579 road|A579]] from Bolton to Leigh. The [[A577 road|A577]] runs from the town to Tyldesley in one direction and to Wigan in the other.\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring towns, villages, and places'''\n|Northwest = [[Westhoughton]]\n|North     = Over Hulton\n|Northeast = [[Little Hulton]]\n|West      = [[Hindley, Greater Manchester|Hindley]]\n|Centre    = Atherton\n|East      = [[Shakerley]]\n|Southwest = [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]]\n|South     = [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]]\n|Southeast = [[Tyldesley]]\n}}\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" id=\"toc\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%; text-align:center\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n!colspan=\"5\"|'''Atherton Compared'''\n|-\n!width=24% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''[[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]]'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''Atherton'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''[[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan|Wigan MB]]'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''[[Greater Manchester Urban Area|GM Urban Area]]'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''England'''\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |Total population||20,302||301,415||2,240,230||49,138,831\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |White||98.5%||98.7%||90.3%||90.9%\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |Asian||0.5%||0.4%||6.2%||4.6%\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |Black||0.2%||0.2%||1.3%||2.3%\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"|Source: Office for National Statistics<ref name=\"2001ethnicdata\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks06--ethnic-group.xls KS06 Ethnic group] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref><ref name=\"2001ethnicdataborough\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211124 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics, Urban area summary results for local authorities|publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-summary-results-for-local-authorities/urban-area-summary-results-for-local-authorities-ks06--ethnic-group.xls KS06 Ethnic group] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n|}\nAt the time of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], according to the [[Office for National Statistics]], the Urban Subdivision of Atherton<ref name=\"2001urbanareamap\">{{Citation |url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/keystats/sqmap.aspx?kv=1371537476&type=-1&title=D90224+:+Greater+Manchester+Urban+Area+-+Atherton+%28urban+area+subdivisions%29 |title=D90224 : Greater Manchester Urban Area \u2013 Atherton (urban area subdivisions) map|publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=24 September 2009}}</ref> was part of the [[Greater Manchester Urban Area]] and had a total resident population of 20,302, of which 9,908 (48.8%) were male and 10,394 (51.2%) were female,<ref name=KS01 /> living in 8,745&nbsp;households.<ref name=\"2001-KS17\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks17--cars-or-vans.xls KS17 Cars or vans] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>  The settlement occupied {{convert|429|ha|sqmi}}, compared with {{convert|431|ha|sqmi}} in the 1991 census.  Its population density was 47.32&nbsp;people per hectare compared with an average of 40.20 across the Greater Manchester Urban Area.<ref name=KS01 />  The median age of the population was 40, compared with 36 within the Greater Manchester Urban Area and 37 across England and Wales.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks02--age-structure.xls KS02 Age structure] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of the population of Atherton were born in England (96.29%); 1.56% were born elsewhere within the United Kingdom, 0.89% within the rest of the European Union, and 1.26% elsewhere in the world.<ref name=\"2001birthdata\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks05--country-of-birth.xls KS05 Country of birth] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n\nData on religious beliefs across the town in the 2001 census show that 86.6% declared themselves to be [[Christians|Christian]], 7.2% said they held no religion, and 0.3% reported themselves as [[Hindu]].<ref name=\"2001religiondata\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks07--religion.xls KS07 Religion] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n\n===Population change===\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;align:center;width:70%;border:0px;text-align:center;line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population growth in Atherton 1777\u20132001\n|-\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Year\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1777\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1801\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1811\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1821\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1831\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1841\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1851\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1861\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1871\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1881\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1891\n|- Align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Population \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 2,200\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 3,249\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 3,894\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,145\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,181\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,475\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,659\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 5,907\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 7,531 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 12,602   \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 15,833  \n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|\n|-\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Year\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1901\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1911\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1921\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1931\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1939\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1951\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1961\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1971\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1981\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1991\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 2001\n|-\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Population \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 16,211\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 18,982\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 19,856\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 19,989 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 20,098\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 20,596\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 19,756 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | <small>''no data''</small> \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 22,032\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 21,696 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 20,302\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|<small>\nParish 1777\u20131861<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nyt.co.uk/athertonhistory.htm |title=Atherton, Lancashire History |publisher=[[Dave Dutton]] |accessdate=24 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120904163825/http://www.nyt.co.uk/athertonhistory.htm |archivedate=4 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Lunn |first=John |title=Atherton Lancashire, A manorial social and industrial history |page=229 |publisher=Atherton UDC |year=1971}}</ref>\n{{\u2022}} Township 1871\u20131891<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10297485&c_id=10001043&add=N |title=Atherton Ch/CP |publisher=Vision of Britain |accessdate=24 July 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026091937/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP |archivedate=26 October 2012 }}</ref> {{\u2022}} Urban District 1901\u20131961<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TOT_POP&u_id=10003209&c_id=10001043&add=N|title=Atherton UD through time. Population Statistics. Total Population|work=A vision of Britain through time|year=2004|author=Great Britain Historical GIS Project|accessdate=21 September 2009|publisher=University of Portsmouth}}</ref> {{\u2022}} Urban Subdivision 1981\u20132001<ref name=\"KS01\">{{citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=24 July 2008|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks01-usual-resident-population.xls KS01 Usual resident population] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=1981 Key Statistics for Urban Areas GB Table 1 |publisher=Office for National Statistics |year=1981}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/greater_manchester_urban_area.asp |title=Greater Manchester Urban Area 1991 Census |publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=7 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108154641/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/greater_manchester_urban_area.asp |archivedate=8 January 2009 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref></small>\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Economy==\nThe northern part of Atherton is within the [[Bolton]] [[Travel to Work Area]], whilst the southern part is within the [[Manchester]] TTWA.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/geography/ttwa.asp |title=Travel to Work Areas |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=24 September 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001231202/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/geography/ttwa.asp |archivedate=1 October 2008 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The town is within the Manchester [[Larger Urban Zone]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/economic_unit/docs/wp13_towards_a_common_standard.pdf |title=Towards a Common Standard |page=29 |format=PDF |publisher=Greater London Authority |accessdate=5 October 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604094316/http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/economic_unit/docs/wp13_towards_a_common_standard.pdf |archivedate=4 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the 2001 Census, there were 8,755&nbsp;people (43.1%) in employment who were resident in Atherton.  Of these, 19.65% worked in the wholesale and retail trades, including repair of motor vehicles; 19.28% worked within manufacturing industry; and 10.27% worked within the health and social work sector.<ref name=\"2001industrydata\">{{citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks11a--industry-of-employment---all-people.xls KS11a Industry of employment \u2013 all people] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref> The census recorded the economic activity of residents aged 16\u201374 as 36.7% in full-time employment, 11.0% in part-time employment, 6.8% self-employed, 4.0% unemployed, 1.7% students with jobs, 3.2% students without jobs, 14.6% retired, 6.5% looking after home or family, 11.8% permanently sick or disabled, and 3.8% economically inactive for other reasons. The 4.0% unemployment rate was high compared with the national rate of 3.3%.<ref>{{citation |title=Economic Activity (UV28) |publisher=Office for National Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6114428&c=atherton&d=14&e=9&g=356872&i=1001x1003x1004&o=56&m=0&r=1&s=1257776525837&enc=1&dsFamilyId=107 |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> According to the Office for National Statistics estimates, during the period between April 2001 and March 2002, the average gross income of households was \u00a3380 per week (\u00a319,760 per year), substantially less than the \u00a3470 per week (\u00a324,440) for the rest of the North West.<ref>{{citation |title=Atherton (Ward), Income: Model-Based Estimates |publisher=Office for National Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6114428&c=atherton&d=14&e=4&g=356872&i=1001x1003x1004&o=56&m=0&r=1&s=1257776100512&enc=1&dsFamilyId=266 |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> The average car ownership per household was 1.01, compared with 0.93 across the Greater Manchester Urban Area; 43.74% of households owned a single car or van, and 30.76% owned none.<ref name=\"2001-KS17\" />\n\nAtherton, the third largest retail centre in the Wigan Borough, has a small pedestrian shopping centre. Most shops front on to Market Street and date from late Victorian times, the majority operated by small independent retailers, although there is a supermarket that brings customers into the town centre. Older, low cost, mostly terraced housing, surrounds the centre of town.<ref>{{citation |title=AthertonTownCentreRegeneration, Current position |url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/Services/Environment/BuiltEnvironment/AthertonTownCentreRegeneration.htm |publisher=wigan.gov.uk |accessdate=10 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119192635/http://www.wigan.gov.uk/Services/Environment/BuiltEnvironment/AthertonTownCentreRegeneration.htm |archivedate=19 November 2009 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bolts and fastenings are still manufactured in Atherton by Smith Bullough, one of a few remaining bolt and nut manufacturers in the UK.<ref name=\"Smith Bullough\">{{citation |url=http://www.smithbullough.com/about_us.html\n|title=Smith Bullough |publisher=smithbullough.com |accessdate=9 November 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091203042045/http://www.smithbullough.com/about_us.html| archivedate= 3 December 2009 |url-status = live}}</ref>\nAs of 2009, a business park is planned for the former Gibfield Colliery site.<ref>{{citation|title=Showcasing our area |url=http://www.andyburnham.org/showcase.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310164052/http://www.andyburnham.org/showcase.asp |url-status = dead|archive-date=10 March 2008 |publisher=andyburnham.org |accessdate=10 October 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:HoweBridge.jpg|thumb|left|220px|[[Howe Bridge]] [[model village]]. The tall building in the centre is the miners' bath house.]]\nThere are several historic [[Listed buildings in Atherton, Greater Manchester|listed buildings]] in and around Atherton, some, but not all, in the area referred to as Chowbent. They include the 17th-century Alder House,<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068470 |desc=Alder House|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> [[Chowbent Chapel]],<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068472 |desc=Chowbent Unitarian Chapel|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> St John the Baptist's Church (1879),<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068475 |desc=Church of St John the Baptist|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> and Chanters Farmhouse,<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1309438 |desc=Chanters Farmhouse |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> all of which are [[listed building]]s. The name \"Chanters\" derives from a [[chantry]] granted by the Bishop of Lichfield in 1360 to Sir William de Atherton. The name is also given to a bridge over the Hindsford Brook and a former colliery.{{sfn|Bond|Ackers|Ward|1979|p=22|ps=none}}\n\t\nA pseudo-[[Ancient Egyptian architecture|Egyptian]] [[obelisk]] near the south-east corner of the parish church, similar to one in Leigh, was probably built for Robert Vernon Atherton in 1781. It was restored in 1867 twelve years before the church was finished. It is a Grade II listed structure.<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1309446  |desc=Obelisk adjacent to south-east corner of Church of St. John the Baptist, Market Place |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1873 and 1875, mineowners Fletcher Burrows built a small [[model village]] at Howe Bridge, comprising cottages, shops, a village club, and a bath house for their employees. This Victorian village on either side of Leigh Road,<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1253226 |desc= 94-118, Leigh Road  |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068474 |desc= 147-191, Leigh Road  |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> together with [[St Michael and All Angels' Church, Howe Bridge|St Michael and All Angel's Church]],<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1268288 |desc= Church of St Michael and All Angels |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> is a [[conservation area]].<ref>{{citation|title=Howe Bridge Conservation Area |url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/27F6B860-A37C-4A85-A8FD-F2C0E8A60194/0/HoweBridgefirstdraft721kb.pdf |publisher=Wigan MBC |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929210425/http://www.wigan.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/27F6B860-A37C-4A85-A8FD-F2C0E8A60194/0/HoweBridgefirstdraft721kb.pdf |archivedate=29 September 2011 |df= }}</ref> The Ena Mill, one of Atherton's large spinning mills, complete with chimney, survives as a reminder of the textile industry.\n\nAtherton's war memorial is a [[cenotaph]] at the intersection of Leigh Road and Hamilton Street was designed by architect [[Arthur John Hope]] and constructed of [[Darley Dale]] stone. It was unveiled in January 1922 by Private J. Roylance, a soldier blinded in action during the [[First World War]].<ref name=\" Atherton Cenotaph designed by A J Hope \">{{citation\n |title=Atherton Cenotaph designed by A J Hope \n |url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/News/Archive/October2007/athertoncenotaph.htm \n |publisher=wigan.gov.uk \n |accessdate=4 April 2010 \n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223075737/http://www.wigan.gov.uk/News/Archive/October2007/athertoncenotaph.htm \n |archivedate=23 February 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe Bolton to Leigh road was [[Turnpike trust|turnpiked]] in about 1770 and a toll gate was installed on the Atherton boundary on Bolton Road.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=119|ps=none}} Shakerley Lane toll road emerged near Green Hall on Bolton Road, and was built to get coal from the [[Shakerley]] pits to the turnpike road.\n\nIn 1825, the [[Bolton and Leigh Railway]] received [[Royal Assent]] and the single track railway was opened in 1828 bringing the railway to the western side of the township where it was close to the coal mines at Howe Bridge and Gibfield. Railway stations opened at [[Atherton Bag Lane railway station|Atherton Bag Lane]] and<ref>{{citation |title=Bag Lane Station |url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/a/atherton/index.shtml |publisher=Subterranea Britannica |accessdate=15 September 2009 }}</ref> further south at [[Atherleigh railway station|Atherleigh]]{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=8|ps=none}} The line was connected to the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] by the Kenyon and Leigh Junction Railway in 1831 and connected to the Tyldesley\u2013Wigan line in 1883 when a station was opened at Chowbent&nbsp;renamed [[Howe Bridge railway station|Howe Bridge]] in 1901.{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=8|ps=none}} The [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]'s line from Manchester to Southport passes to the north of Atherton and [[Atherton railway station|Atherton Station]] which was opened in 1887\u201388 remains open.<ref>{{Cite PastScape |num=499048 |desc=Monument no. 499048 |access-date=17 September 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Atherton railway station in 1989.jpg|thumb|right|220px|[[Atherton railway station]]]]\nIn 1900, a Bill authorising the [[South Lancashire Tramways]] Company to construct over {{convert|62|mi|km}} of tramway in southern Lancashire was given Royal Assent.<ref name=\"Lancashire United\">{{citation |title=History |url=http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |publisher=lancashireunited.org.uk |accessdate=1 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006172556/http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |archive-date=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \nHowever, by November 1900 the South Lancashire Electric Traction and Power Company had acquired the shares. The first section of tramway opened on 20 October 1902 between [[Lowton]] and Four Lanes Ends via Leigh and Atherton. The company got into financial difficulty and in turn became Lancashire United Tramways later [[Lancashire United Transport]] (LUT). LUT had headquarters and a large depot in Howe Bridge. On 16 December 1933, the last tram ran from Leigh to Four Lane Ends. The following day trolley buses took over.<ref>{{citation |title=LUT |url=http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |publisher=lancashireunited.org.uk |accessdate=31 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006172556/http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |archive-date=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nPublic transport in Atherton is co-ordinated by the [[Transport for Greater Manchester]].\nThere are public transport links by rail from Atherton and [[Hag Fold railway station|Hag Fold]] stations to [[Wigan Wallgate railway station|Wigan]] and [[Manchester Victoria railway station|Manchester]] operated by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]], and by bus to [[Bolton]], [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], [[Wigan]], Manchester, the [[Trafford Centre]] and [[Middlebrook, Greater Manchester|Middlebrook Retail and Leisure Complex]] operated by [[Diamond Bus North West]] of Atherton, [[Stagecoach Manchester]] and [[First Greater Manchester]].\n\nAtherton is also known for the Vantage V2 bus service by [[First Greater Manchester]].<ref>{{Diff|en:Leigh-Salford-Manchester_Bus_Rapid_Transit|diff=|oldid=917506291|label=en:Leigh-Salford-Manchester_Bus_Rapid_Transit,   oldid 917506291}}{{Circular reference|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{Further|List of schools in Wigan}}\nThe first school in Atherton was Chowbent Grammar School founded before 1654,<ref name=vch/> followed by Chowbent Chapel School in 1734. [[National school (England and Wales)|Lane Top National School]] opened in 1840 and Chowbent Unitarian School and Hindsford St Anne's in 1860. Howe Bridge School opened in 1869 and St Philip's a year later. An undenominational school in Lee Street opened in 1871 followed by St George's and Sacred Heart School in Hindsford in 1873. In the 1890s, the technical school originally opened as a school for science and art, followed by St Richard's in 1891 and Flapper Fold Higher Grade School in 1893. Green Hall Special School opened in 1957, and a new infant school was opened on Lodge Lane for Sacred Heart. Meadowbank Primary School can also be found on Flapper Fold Lane, marking the boundary between Atherton and Hag Fold. Hesketh Fletcher Senior School opened in 1967{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=Appendix 24|ps=none}} and closed on 31 August 2011. [[Atherton Community School]] opened in 2012.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/greater-manchesters-first-free-school-694344 |title=Greater Manchester's first free school opens in Atherton |publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=3 September 2012 |accessdate=1 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110180101/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/greater-manchesters-first-free-school-694344 |archivedate=10 January 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\n<div style=\"font-size: 95%\">\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n|+List of schools in Atherton \n! School\n! Locality\n! Description\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Ofsted\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Website\n|-\n| Atherton St George's C.E. Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|130300|130300}}\n| [http://www.saintgeorges.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Chowbent Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106443|106443}}\n| [http://www.chowbent.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Hindsford C.E. Primary School\n| Hindsford, Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106441|106441}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20110514154951/http://www.hindsford.wigan.sch.uk/general_info.html website]\n|-\n| Meadowbank Primary and Nursery School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106425|106425}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100523062340/http://www.meadowbank.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Parklee Community School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106426|106426}}\n| [http://www.parklee.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Sacred Heart R.C. Primary School\n| Hindsford, Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106499|106499}}\n| [http://www.athertonsacredheart.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| St Michael's C.E. Primary School, Howe Bridge\n| Howe Bridge, Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106478|106478}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100222021321/http://www.howebridge.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| St Philip's C.E. Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106515|106515}}\n| [http://www.saintphilips.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| St Richard's Catholic Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106498|106498}}\n| [http://www.saintrichards.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Hesketh Fletcher C.E. High School (closed)\n| Atherton\n| Secondary school\n| {{ofsted|106536|106536}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100411080859/http://www.heskethfletcher.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| New Greenhall School\n| Atherton\n| Special school\n| {{ofsted|131295|131295}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20120307004235/http://www.newgreenhall.wigan.sch.uk/index.htm website]\n|-\n|}\n</div>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St John's, Atherton 02.jpg|thumb|left|The tower of [[Church of St John the Baptist, Atherton|Atherton Parish Church]]]]\n{{See also|List of churches in Greater Manchester}}\n\nThree chapels or churches have been built on the site of the Parish [[Church of St John the Baptist, Atherton|Church of St John the Baptist]]. A chapel was built in 1645 by John Atherton. It is sometimes referred to as the Old Bent Chapel.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=37|ps=none}} It remained unconsecrated and was used by the [[Presbyterian]]s.<ref name=vch/> In 1721 Richard Atherton expelled the [[dissenter]]s and the chapel was consecrated in 1723 by the [[Bishop of Sodor and Man]]. A new chapel on the site was consecrated by the [[Bishop of Chester]] in 1814. The present church dedicated to [[John the Baptist|St John the Baptist]] was consecrated in 1879.<ref name=vch/> The church, designed by [[Hubert Austin|Austin]] and [[Edward Graham Paley|Paley]], is built in [[Runcorn]] stone. It is {{convert|60|ft}} wide, {{convert|127|ft}} long, and the {{convert|24|ft|adj=on}} square tower rises to {{convert|120|ft}}. The fabric of the church has suffered from mining [[subsidence]].\n\nThe New Bent or [[Chowbent Chapel]], the earliest [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|Nonconformist]] chapel in Atherton, was built in 1721 and opened in 1722.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=37|ps=none}} The chapel was built by the Presbyterian congregation after it was expelled from the first chapel.<ref name=vch/>\n\nA mission occupying a barn in Hindsford was replaced in 1901 by [[St Anne's Church, Hindsford|St Anne's Church]] designed by Austin and Paley.<ref name=vch/> It has since been converted to residential use. [[St Michael and All Angels' Church, Howe Bridge|St Michael and All Angels]] at Howe Bridge was built in 1877.<ref name=vch/> There are chapels of the [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan]], [[Baptist]], Independent [[Methodist]], and Primitive Methodist denominations; a Congregational Church at Howe Bridge was opened in 1904.<ref name=vch/> Roman Catholics celebrated mass in a loft behind the Star and Garter public house on Tyldesley Square until [[Sacred Heart Roman Catholic Church, Hindsford|Sacred Heart Church]] opened in Hindsford in 1869. The site was given by Lord Lilford and building materials were donated by John Holland, manager of [[Yew Tree Colliery]] in Tyldesley. It served the growing Catholic population in Hindsford and Tyldesley.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=180|ps=none}} Sacred Heart closed in 2004, and its parish together with St Richard's in Mayfield Street which opened in 1928, Holy Family in [[Boothstown]], St Ambrose Barlow in [[Astley, Greater Manchester|Astley]], St Gabriel's, Higher Folds in Leigh were united as a single community with [[Margaret Clitherow|St Margaret Clitherow]] as its patron.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.leighpastoralarea.co.uk/index.php/information |title=The Catholic Church in the Leigh Area |publisher=Leigh Pastoral Area |accessdate=28 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213040807/http://www.leighpastoralarea.co.uk/index.php/information |archivedate=13 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.sacredheartrchindsford.co.uk/history.html |title=History |publisher=sacredheartrchindsford.co.uk |accessdate=28 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815042815/http://sacredheartrchindsford.co.uk/history.html |archivedate=15 August 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\nSwimming baths opened in Mayfield Street in 1902 and a swimming club was formed. The baths closed in 2005 and the Atherton & Leigh Amateur Swimming Club moved to the new [[Leigh Sports Village]] facility in 2008.<ref name=\"Atherton Swimming Club FC\">{{citation |url=http://www.athertonsc.org.uk/web/new_web/home_page.htm |title=Atherton Swimming Club |publisher=athertonsc.org.uk |accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nAtherton has two semi-pro football teams, the oldest of which is [[Atherton Collieries A.F.C.]], formed in 1916, who play in the [[Northern Premier League]].<ref name=\"Atherton Collieries FC\">{{citation|url=http://www.pyramidpassion.co.uk/html/atherton_collieries.html|title=Atherton Collieries |publisher=pyramidpassion.co.uk |accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref> \nOthers are [[Atherton Laburnum Rovers F.C.]], members of the North West Counties Football League<ref name=\"Laburnum Rovers FC\">{{citation|url=http://www.athertonlr.co.uk/details.htm|title=AthertonLR|publisher=athertonlr.co.uk|accessdate=28 September 2009|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080522093733/http://www.athertonlr.co.uk/details.htm |archivedate = 22 May 2008}}</ref>\nand Atherton Town FC.<ref name=\"Atherton Town FC\">{{citation |url=http://www.athertontownfc.co.uk/|title=Atherton Town |publisher=athertontownfc.co.uk |accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nAtherton Cricket Club was formed in 1872 and has played in the Bolton and District Cricket Association since 1921.<ref name=\"Atherton Cricket Club\">{{citation|url=http://atherton.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp?|title=Atherton Cricket Club|publisher=atherton.play-cricket.com/|accessdate=2 January 2012|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130223194247/http://atherton.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp |archivedate=23 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Public services==\nAtherton is policed by the [[Greater Manchester Police]] force from Atherton Police Station, \nwhich covers Atherton, Tyldesley, Astley and Mosley Common, and is one of 5 subdivisions within the Wigan division.<ref name=\"gmp\">{{citation|url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/live/nhoodv3.nsf/index-communities.html?ReadForm&Division=Wigan&Area=Atherton |title=Police Atherton |publisher=Greater Manchester Police |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808011831/http://www.gmp.police.uk/live/Nhoodv3.nsf/index-communities.html?ReadForm&Division=Wigan&Area=Atherton |archivedate=8 August 2010 |df= }}</ref>\nIt is part of the L division, which covers the entirety of Wigan borough.\nThe statutory emergency fire and rescue service is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]], \nfrom Atherton  fire station.<ref name=\"fire\">{{citation |url= http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/wigan.aspx|title= Fire and Rescue |publisher= Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue|accessdate=24 May 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080612052419/http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/wigan.aspx |archivedate = 12 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nHealth services in the Wigan borough are provided by the Wigan Borough Clinical Commissioning Group.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.wiganboroughccg.nhs.uk/|title= Welcome to the Wigan Borough Clinical Commissioning Group Website |publisher= Wigan Borough Clinical Commissioning Group|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> Hospital services are provided by the Wrightington, Wigan and Leigh NHS Foundation Trust who provide an [[Emergency department|Accident and Emergency]] service at Wigan's Royal Albert Edward Infirmary and outpatient clinics at Leigh Infirmary.<ref name=\"W&Lnhs\">{{citation |url= http://www.wiganleigh.nhs.uk/|title= Wigan and Leigh NHS |publisher= Wigan and Leigh NHS|accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nWaste management is co-ordinated by the Wigan Authority, which is a statutory waste disposal authority in its own right.<ref name=\"gmwda\">{{citation |url= http://www.gmwda.gov.uk/|title=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority|publisher= gmwda.gov.uk|accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref>\nAtherton's Distribution Network Operator for electricity is Electricity North West Ltd.<ref name=\"grid\">{{citation |url=  http://www.nationalgrid.com/uk/Electricity/AboutElectricity/DistributionCompanies/|title=Electricity Distribution Companies|publisher=nationalgrid.com/uk|accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref>\nUnited Utilities manages Atherton's drinking and waste water.<ref name=\"UU\">{{citation|url=http://www.unitedutilities.com/index.htm |title=United Utilities |publisher=United Utilities |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102043849/http://unitedutilities.com/index.htm |archivedate=2 January 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nAtherton Botanical Garden Club, which is today a social club, was formed in 1850, and organised lectures, study groups and rambles on [[Chat Moss]] for its members.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=176|ps=none}} A public library was opened in 1905 with an [[Andrew Carnegie]] grant.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=199|ps=none}} Bent Chapel already had a library in the Chowbent School, and donated 4,000&nbsp;books to the new town library.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=93|ps=none}} Central Park, a {{convert|10|acre|adj=on}} public park, was created in 1912. Other parks were later provided in Lodge Lane, Hindsford and Devonshire Place. The urban district council also acquired the grounds belonging to Howe Bridge Welfare in 1963.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=200|ps=none}} In the early and mid-20th century Atherton had three cinemas, the Gem in Bullough Street, the Savoy and the Palace on Market Street.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=198|ps=none}} An amateur photographic society was formed in 1938.<ref name=\"ADAPS\">{{citation |url=http://www.adaps.org.uk/|title=Atherton & District Amateur Photographic Society |publisher=adaps.org |accessdate=24 September 2009}}</ref> Formby Hall, demolished in 2018, used to host the ''Bent 'n' Bongs'' [[Beer Festival]] over the last weekend of every January.\n\n==Notable residents==\nThere were several ministers of note of [[Chowbent Chapel]] including James Wood, the \"General\" (1672\u20131759), who distinguished himself at the [[Battle of Preston (1715)|Battle of Preston]] in 1715.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=23|ps=none}} [[Thomas Walker Horsfield]]<ref>{{citation |title=Thomas Walker Horsfield |url=http://theweald.org/N10.asp?Nid=2181 |publisher=The Weald.org |accessdate=20 September 2009 }}</ref> (1792\u20131837) was a historian and topographer. [[Joseph Nightingale]] (1775\u20131824), born in Chowbent, was a prolific English writer and [[preacher]] who subsequently became a Unitarian.\n[[Eric Laithwaite]] (1921\u20131997) was an engineer, principally known for his development of the [[linear induction motor]] and [[Maglev]] rail system.<ref>{{citation |title= Obituary \u2013 Professor Eric Laithwaite |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/publications/reporterarchive/0055/feat03.htm  |publisher=Imperial College |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> Chess grandmaster [[Nigel Short]] grew up in Atherton and attended St Philip's School.<ref>{{citation |title= Nigel Short |url=http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=2426 |publisher=chessbase.com|accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> Architect [[Arthur John Hope]] (1875\u20131960), a partner in [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] was born and lived in Atherton.<ref name=\" Atherton Cenotaph designed by A J Hope \"/> [[Edward Ormerod]], mining engineer at Gib Field Colliery, invented the Ormerod detaching hook, an important mining safety device.<ref>{{citation | url=http://www.edwardormerodandco.co.uk/history.html|title= Edward Ormerod and Co Ltd|accessdate =27 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nAndy Whyment, Coronation Street actor (Kirk Sutherland) and runner up of I'm a celebrity 2019\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Atherton, Greater Manchester]]\n*[[List of people from Wigan]]\n*[[List of mills in Wigan]]\n*[[List of mining disasters in Lancashire]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation |last1=Bond |first1= |last2=Ackers |first2= |last3=Ward |first3= |title=Leigh Homesteads |publisher=Leigh Local History Society Publication No7 |year=1979}}\n*{{citation |last=Holcroft |first=Fred |title=Silk Manufacturing in Leigh |publisher=Leigh Local History Society Publication No21 |year=1998}}\n*{{citation |last=Lunn |first=John |title=Atherton Lancashire, A manorial social and industrial history |publisher=Atherton UDC |year=1971}}\n*{{citation |last=Mills |first=A. D. |title=Dictionary of English Place-Names |publisher=Oxford |year=1998 |isbn=0-19-280074-4 |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/views/ENTRY.html?entry=t40.e651&srn=1&ssid=931364015#FIRSTHIT}} {{Subscription}} \n*{{citation |last1=Pollard |first1=Richard |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |last3=Sharples |first3=Joseph |title=Lancashire: Liverpool and the South West |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-10910-8}}}\n*{{citation |last=Sweeney |first=D. J. |title=A Lancashire Triangle Part One |publisher=Triangle Publishing |year=1996 |isbn=0-9529333-0-6}}\n*{{citation |last=Sweeney |first=D. J. |title=A Lancashire Triangle Part Two |publisher=Triangle Publishing |year=1997 |isbn=0-9529333-2-2}}\n*{{citation |last=Wright |first=J. J. |title=The Story of Chowbent Chapel |publisher=Chowbent Chapel |year=1921}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Atherton, Greater Manchester}}\n*[http://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Atherton/index.html  Atherton at lan-opc]\n* {{Genuki|county=LAN|Atherton}}\n*[http://www.mortfamily.net/ Mort family, Alder House]\n{{Greater Manchester}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Atherton, Greater Manchester| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Geography of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                 England     \n|official_name=            Atherton\n|coordinates = {{coord|53.523|-2.495|display=inline,title}}\n|population=               22,000\n|population_ref=<ref name=WiganCore>{{citation |title=Wigan Core Strategy 2013|publisher=Wigan Council|url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/Docs/PDF/Council/Strategies-Plans-and-Policies/Planning/Adopted-Core-Strategy.pdf|accessdate=12 February 2014|date=30 September 2013}}</ref>\n|metropolitan_borough=     [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan|Wigan]]\n|metropolitan_county=      [[Greater Manchester]]\n|region =                  North West England  \n|constituency_westminster= [[Bolton West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolton West]]        \n|constituency_westminster1= [[Leigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Leigh]]\n|post_town=                MANCHESTER\n|postcode_district =       M46  \n|postcode_area=            M  \n|dial_code=                01942\n|os_grid_reference=        SD672030\n|london_distance=          {{convert|171|mi|km|0|abbr=on}}&nbsp;[[Boxing the compass|SSE]]\n|static_image_name=        Market Street, Atherton.jpg\n|static_image_caption=     Market Street\n}}\n\n'''Atherton''' (pop. 20,300) is a town in the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]], in [[Greater Manchester]], England and [[Historic counties of England|historically]] was historically a part of [[Lancashire]]. The town,  including [[Hindsford]], [[Howe Bridge]] and [[Hag Fold railway station|Hag Fold]], is {{convert|5|mi|km|1}} east of [[Wigan]], {{convert|2|mi|km|1}} north of [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], and {{convert|10.7|mi|km|1}} northwest of [[Manchester]]. From the 17th century, for about 300 years, Atherton was known as Chowbent, which was frequently shortened to Bent, the town's old nickname.\n\nAtherton was associated with coal mining and nail manufacture from the 14th century, encouraged by outcropping coal seams. At the beginning of the 20th century the town was described as \"the centre of a district of collieries, cotton mills and iron-works, which cover the surface of the country with their inartistic buildings and surroundings, and are linked together by the equally unlovely dwellings of the people\".<ref name=vch/> Atherton's last deep coal mine closed in 1966, and the last working cotton mills closed in 1999. Today the town is the third largest retail centre in the Borough of Wigan; almost 20% of those employed in the area work in the wholesale and retail trades, although there is still some significant manufacturing industry in the town.\n\nEvidence has been discovered of a [[Roman Britain|Roman]] road passing through the area, on the ancient route between Coccium (Wigan) and [[Mamucium]] (Manchester). Following the [[Anglo-Saxon settlement of Britain|Anglo-Saxon]] invasion of England, Atherton, which is built on and around seven brooks, became part of the manor of [[Warrington]] until the [[Norman conquest]], when it became a township or [[vill]] in the ancient parish of Leigh.<ref name=\"GENUKI Parish map\">{{citation |title=Atherton map|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Atherton/ParishMap.shtml |publisher=genuki.org.uk |accessdate=31 August 2009}}</ref> Since 1974 the town has been part of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, a local government district of the [[metropolitan county|Metropolitan County]] of [[Greater Manchester]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Toponymy===\nAtherton was recorded as Aderton in 1212 and 1242, and Atherton in 1259.<ref name=vch>{{citation |last1= Farrer |first1=William |last2=Brownbill |first2= J. (editors) |title=Atherton |url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=41363 |work=A History of the County of Lancaster: Volume 3 |publisher=[[Victoria County History]] |pages=435\u2013439 |year=1907 |accessdate=28 August 2009}}</ref>\nOpinions differ as to the derivation of the name. One is the farmstead or village of a man named Aethelhere, an [[Old English]] personal name and the suffix ''tun'', meaning an enclosure, farmstead or manor estate;<ref>{{Harvnb|Mills|1998|p=10}}</ref><ref>{{Harvnb|Mills|1998|p=406}}</ref> another is ''adre'', Saxon for little brook with the suffix ''tun''.<ref name=\"Lunn1971, p.1\">{{Harvnb|Lunn|1971|p=1}}</ref> Either is possible as Atherton is bounded by brooks to the west and south, and crossed by several others. The western boundary is [[Hindsford]] Brook, originally named Goderic Brook after a [[Saxon]] saint.<ref name=\"Lunn1971, p.2\">{{Harvnb|Lunn|1971|p=2}}</ref>\n\nThe Chow&nbsp;\u2013 recorded as Chew, Cholle and Chowl&nbsp;\u2013 family were tenants of the Athertons living at the valley by Chanters Brook. This part of the township became known as Chow's Bent but the meaning of Bent has been lost, perhaps a bend or slope. It was referred to in the 14th century as Chollebynt or Shollebent.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=15|ps=none}} Chowbent, or Bent, was the name given to the built-up part of Atherton from the mid-17th century for at least 300&nbsp;years.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=10|ps=none}}  As the population grew, the town was called Atherton, although the names ''Chowbent'' or ''Bent'' are used by locals.\n\n===Early history===\nEvidence of a Roman road and [[Bronze Age]] settlement have been found in the area.<ref name=\"WAS\">{{citation |title=Newsletter 66|url=http://www.wiganarchsoc.co.uk/content/News_Letters/news066.htm|publisher=wiganarchsoc.co.uk |accessdate=30 November 2009}}</ref> The Roman road between Manchester and Wigan is shown on the 1849 6\" [[Ordnance Survey|OS map]] crossing Miller's Lane at 90&nbsp;degrees about halfway down.<ref name=\"Wigan Archaeological Society\">{{citation |title=Newsletter 71|url=http://www.wiganarchsoc.co.uk/content/News_Letters/news071.htm|publisher=wiganarchsoc.co.uk |accessdate=7 September 2009}}</ref> The site of Gadbury Brickworks at [[Gibfield Colliery]] has been excavated, and evidence of Roman and possibly earlier settlements found.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=2146411154|title=Dig unearths ancient settlement and Roman road |publisher=megalithic.co.uk |accessdate=10 October 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Manor===\n[[File:Joseph Wright - Mrs. Robert Gwillym.jpg|thumb|upright|Richard Atherton's daughter Elizabeth, Mrs Robert Gwillym, painted by [[Joseph Wright of Derby]]]]\nThe [[manorialism|manor]] was held by the Atherton family from the de Botelers, whose chief manor was at [[Warrington]].<ref name=vch/> William and Nicholas Atherton fought at the [[Battle of Agincourt]] in 1415.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=9|ps=none}} The manor house was situated towards the south of the ancient [[Township (England)|township]]. [[Christopher Saxton]]'s map shows a [[medieval deer park]] in the time of [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth I]].<ref name=vch/><ref>{{citation |publisher= ancestry.com |title=Christopher Saxton's 1579 map |url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/~genmaps/genfiles/COU_files/ENG/LAN/saxton_lancs_1579.htm |accessdate=16 September 2009 }}</ref>  \"Mad\" Richard Atherton, the last direct male descendant of the Athertons is remembered for two events; his expulsion of the congregation from the first Atherton Chapel in 1721,{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=99|ps=none}} and building [[Atherton Hall, Leigh|Atherton Hall]] on a grand scale, to designs by architect William Wakefield. Work on the hall started in 1723 and was not finished until 1743.{{sfn|Pollard|Pevsner|Sharples|2006|p=140|ps=none}} The carriage drive from the hall led over Lion's Bridge down an avenue to gates which faced [[Church of St Mary the Virgin, Leigh|the parish church in Leigh]] where the Athertons had a chapel.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=111|ps=none}} Richard Vernon Atherton was the last of the Atherton male line. He married Elizabeth Farington and had a daughter named Elizabeth.\n\nThe Atherton family's association with the township ended with Richard Atherton's death in 1726. His daughter, Elizabeth, married Robert Gwillym and their son, Robert Vernon Atherton, married Henrietta Maria Legh. They had five children; the sons died young, and their eldest daughter Henrietta Maria Atherton married Thomas Powys, 2nd Baron Lilford<ref>{{Harvnb|Lunn|1971|p=128}}</ref> whose father was ennobled by [[Pitt the Younger]] in 1797, taking the title of [[Baron Lilford]]. He left his estates to his son, [[Thomas Powys, 3rd Baron Lilford|Thomas Atherton Powys]]. The Atherton estate was inherited by Lord Lilford, who preferred to live at his family seat, [[Lilford Hall]] in Northamptonshire. Lord Lilford could not afford the upkeep of another house and Atherton Hall was put up for sale but, after failing to sell, it was demolished in 1824. Some outbuildings were left standing and are private property still known as Atherton Hall.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=160|ps=none}} This portion of Atherton was incorporated into [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]] in 1894 and the area became a public park.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=195|ps=none}}\n\n===Two battles===\nThe area was divided in its allegiance during the [[English Civil War|Civil War]]. In 1642, men of Chowbent were on their way to Leigh Church when word came that [[James Stanley, 7th Earl of Derby]]'s [[Cavalier|Royalist]] troops were marching through Leigh, probably en route for Manchester. The men of Chowbent armed themselves and drove the Earl's men back to Lowton Common, killing some, wounding others and taking prisoner about 200 men: \"...&nbsp;we are all upon our guard, and the Naylors of Chowbent, instead of making Nayles, have busied themselves making Bills and Battle Axes.\" (Civil War tracts of Lancashire, Chetham Society Series, vol II).{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=27|ps=none}}\n\nIn 1715, during the [[Jacobite rising of 1715|Jacobite rising]] the supporters of the [[Old Pretender]] were marching on [[Preston, Lancashire|Preston]]. General [[Charles Wills]] wrote to [[James Wood (minister)|Minister Wood]] of Atherton Chapel asking him to raise a force to be at [[Cuerden Green]] the following day, 12 November.<ref>{{Harvnb|Wright|1921|p=28}}</ref>  Minister Wood led a force of Chowbent men who were given the job of guarding the bridge over the [[River Ribble]] at [[Walton-le-Dale]] and a ford at [[Penwortham]], which they defended successfully. The Highlanders were routed, and for his efforts Parson James Wood was given a \u00a3100 [[Life annuity|annuity]] (equivalent to \u00a3{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|100|1715|r=-2}}}} in {{Inflation-year|UK}}){{Inflation-fn|UK|df=y}} by Parliament and the title \"The General\" by his congregation.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=31|ps=none}}\n\n===Industrial history===\nAtherton, along with neighbouring [[Shakerley]], was associated with coal mining and nail manufacture. Alexander Naylor was taxed on his goods in 1332, showing the industry was present for at least 600&nbsp;years. Encouraged by the proximity of outcrops of coal, iron was brought from Derbyshire, Yorkshire and Spain. Several types of nails were made, including [[lath]] nails, [[slate]] nails, thatching nails and sparrowbills. The nail smithies manufactured [[plough]]s and [[scythe]]s; their products were taken by [[pack horse]] to be sold in Manchester, [[Denbigh]], [[Clitheroe]] and [[Kendal]].{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=19|ps=none}} The nail industry developed into the manufacture of nuts and bolts. Thomas Blakemore was the first in 1843 and by 1853 there were eight manufacturers of nuts and bolts including James Prestwich and Robert Parker.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=171|ps=none}} Some nut and bolt manufacturers also made spindles and flyers for spinning machinery.<ref name=vch/> Collier Brook Bolt Works on Bag Lane dating from 1856 survives and is a Grade II listed building.<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068454 |desc=Collier Brook Bolt House|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2}}</ref>\n\nCoal had been mined for several hundred years in numerous shallow shafts and [[adit]]s, but took on greater importance when in 1776 Robert Vernon Atherton leased the coal rights to Thomas Guest from Leigh and John Fletcher from [[Bolton]].{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=117|ps=none}} In 1845 the era of deep mining commenced with the sinking of Fletcher's Lover's Lane pit at [[Howe Bridge]]. The Crombouke Day-Eye, a drift mine accessing the shallow Brassy and [[Crombouke mine]]s, opened in 1870 and closed in 1907. (A coal seam was referred to as a \"mine\" in this part of Lancashire.) By the early 1870s [[Fletcher, Burrows and Company]]'s [[Howe Bridge Colliery]], the biggest of the three Howe Bridge pits, was sunk to the Black & White, or Seven Foot mine. The pit closed in 1959.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=187|ps=none}}{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=38|ps=none}} [[Gibfield Colliery]], situated alongside the [[Bolton and Leigh Railway]], was working in 1829, and coal was mined from the [[Trencherbone mine]].{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=33|ps=none}} Forty years later a {{convert|1169|ft|adj=on}} shaft was sunk to Arley Mine. The pit closed in 1963. In September 1913 the first pit head baths in the country were opened at Gibfield. [[Chanters Colliery]] was in [[Hindsford]], where {{convert|1120|ft|adj=on}} shafts were sunk to the Trencherbone mine in 1854.{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=328|ps=none}} In the late 1890s shafts were deepened to {{convert|1800|ft}} to reach the Arley mine. Atherton had its share of mining disasters \u2014 on 11 February 1850 five men died in a gas explosion caused by a lighted candle at Gibfield,<ref>{{citation|title=Gibfield Colliery Disaster |url=http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1850_54.pdf |format=PDF |page=1 |publisher=cmhrc.co.uk |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613010419/http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1850_54.pdf |archivedate=13 June 2010 |df=dmy }}</ref> and 27 men died at Lovers Lane Colliery after a [[firedamp]] explosion caused by blown-out shot on 28 March 1872.<ref>{{citation |title=Lovers Lane Disaster Disaster|url=  http://www.dmm.org.uk/names/d1870-79.htm| publisher=dmm.org.uk |accessdate=17 October 2009}}</ref> On 6 March 1957 eight men died at Chanters Colliery after an explosion of gas.<ref>{{citation|title=Chanters Colliery Disaster |url=http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1952_57.pdf |page=14 |publisher=cmhrc.co.uk |accessdate=17 October 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100613010347/http://www.cmhrc.co.uk/cms/document/1952_57.pdf |archivedate=13 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> \nChanters closed in 1966 bringing the era of deep coal mining in the town to an end.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=205|ps=none}}\nIn 1908, the Lancashire and Cheshire Coal Owners Association opened [[Howe Bridge Mines Rescue Station]].<ref>{{citation |title=Howe Bridge Mines Rescue |url=http://www.colsal.org.uk/sites/lancashireminesrescue/HOWEBRIDGEMRS.asp |publisher=colsal.org.uk |accessdate=14 September 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:EnaMill.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Ena Mill in 2000]]\nThe [[cotton mill]]s grew out of a cottage spinning and weaving industry that was widespread across the district. As industrialisation gathered pace, local [[Weaver (occupation)|weavers]] felt threatened by the advent of powered [[loom]]s, and in April 1812 a mob smashed the machines and burnt down a new factory, [[Westhoughton Mill]], in neighbouring [[Westhoughton]]. For this, the [[Luddite]]s, three men and a boy of 14, were tried at [[Lancaster Castle|Lancaster Assizes]] and hanged.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=152|ps=none}} [[Fustian]] was woven and after 1827 silk<ref name=vch/> also was brought from Manchester.{{sfn|Holcroft|1998|p=10|ps=none}} In 1938 [[James Burton (millowner)|James Burton]] had built [[cotton mill]]s on both sides of the Hindsford Brook including Lodge Mill. Dan Lane Spinning and Doubling Mills were built in the 1840s and lasted until the 1950s. Howe Bridge Spinning Mills, the largest complex in Atherton was started in 1868 and the last mill built in 1919. It closed as a textile factory in early 1999.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=180|ps=none}}  Mills built in the 20th century were Laburnum Mills in 1905 (closed 1980), and Ena Mill in 1908 which closed in 1999. The Ena Mill, now converted for other uses, is a Grade II [[listed building]].{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=199|ps=none}}<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1253159 |desc=Ena Mill|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\n[[File:Atherton Town Hall - geograph.org.uk - 1548868.jpg|thumb|Atherton Town Hall]]\nAtherton is an electoral ward of the [[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]. The ward elects three councillors to the 75-member metropolitan borough council, Wigan's [[local authority]]. As of 2019 Councillors in all three local wards are Independents.<ref name=ward>{{citation |title=Councillor & Committee Details |url=http://democracy.wigan.gov.uk/mgMemberIndex.aspx?bcr=1 |publisher=wigan.gov.uk|author=Wigan Metropolitan Borough Council|accessdate=28 August 2016}}</ref> \nHistorically, Atherton was in the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|Hundred]] of [[West Derby (hundred)|West Derby]], a judicial division of southwest Lancashire. Atherton was one of the six townships or [[vill]]s that made up the ancient ecclesiastical parish of Leigh.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=1|ps=none}} The townships existed before the parish. The manor of Atherton was held by the Atherton family from the de Botelers, whose chief manor was at [[Warrington]].<ref name=vch/>\n\nUnder the terms of the [[Poor Law Amendment Act 1834]] the townships were part of the Leigh [[Poor Law Union]] which was established on 26 January 1837 comprising an area covering the whole of the ancient parish of Leigh and part of [[Winwick, Cheshire|Winwick]]. Workhouses existed in [[Pennington, Greater Manchester|Pennington]], [[Culcheth]], [[Tyldesley]], [[Lowton]] and Hag Fold in Atherton, but the [[Leigh Union workhouse]] at Atherleigh replaced them in the 1850s.<ref name=Workhouses>{{citation |title=Leigh |url= http://www.workhouses.org.uk/Leigh/|publisher=workhouses.org.uk |accessdate=31 August 2009}}</ref> In 1863 the Local Government Act 1858 was adopted for the township, meaning it was governed by a [[local board of health]], a type of regulatory body responsible for standards of hygiene and sanitation in the township. In 1894 part of the township was added to Leigh Urban District; the remainder became [[Atherton Urban District]]. The [[Urban district (Great Britain and Ireland)|urban district]] was abolished in 1974 under the [[Local Government Act 1972]], when the area became part of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan, a local government district of the [[metropolitan county]] of [[Greater Manchester]].<ref name=\"GM Gazetteer A\">{{citation |url=http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazza.htm |title=Greater Manchester Gazetteer |publisher=Greater Manchester County Record Office|accessdate=3 June 2010|archivedate=18 July 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718144214/http://www.gmcro.co.uk/Guides/Gazeteer/gazza.htm}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a review of parliamentary representation in Greater Manchester, Atherton is part of the [[Bolton West (UK Parliament constituency)|Bolton West]] Parliamentary constituency. It is the only ward in the borough to be represented outside a Wigan borough seat (the remainder of the borough is represented by Leigh, Makerfield or Wigan).<ref name=\"About Bolton West\">{{citation|url=http://www.labouronline.org/wibs/165798/e10eff00-8855-3bf4-6d31-76d6329f2426|title=Bolton West |publisher=labouronline.org |accessdate=8 November 2009}}</ref> Atherton's MP is [[Chris Green (politician)|Chris Green]] of the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] who won the parliamentary seat for Bolton West in the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref name=\"Election 2015\">{{citation|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000580|title=Election 2015: Bolton West|accessdate=28 August 2016|work=BBC News}}</ref> Howe Bridge is in the [[Leigh (UK Parliament constituency)|Leigh]] constituency represented by [[James Grundy]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)]]).\n\n==Geography==\n{{Further|Geography of Greater Manchester}}\n{{climate chart|Atherton\n|1|6|70\n|1|7|50\n|3|9|60\n|4|12|50\n|7|15|60\n|10|18|70\n|12|20|70\n|12|20|80\n|10|17|70\n|8|14|80\n|4|9|80\n|2|7|80\n|float=right\n|source={{citation |url=http://weather.yahoo.com/climo/UKXX1090_f.html?woeid=11353 |year=2008 |title=Atherton Weather |accessdate=9 November 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110608235905/http://weather.yahoo.com/climo/UKXX1090_f.html?woeid=11353 |archive-date=8 June 2011 |url-status = dead }}\n|clear=both\n}} \nAt {{coord|53|31|23|N|2|29|44|W|type:city}} (53.5231\u00b0, \u22122.4955\u00b0), and {{convert|171|mi|km|0}} northwest of [[central London]], Atherton is situated {{convert|5|mi}} east of Wigan and {{convert|10.7|mi}} west-northwest of the city of Manchester, at the eastern end of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan.\n\nAtherton, which includes Hindsford to the southeast, [[Howe Bridge]] in the southwest, and Hag Fold in the north, is generally low lying. The soil is clay in much of the township.<ref name=vch/> The southwest of the town is {{convert|100|ft}} above sea level, rising to {{convert|250|ft}} in the north.<ref name=vch/> Atherton is built around seven brooks: the Shakerley Brook forms the western boundary with Tyldesley; Chanters Brook flows through the area known as \"The Valley\"; Knight's Brook (Bag Lane); Colliers Brook; Small Brook is the boundary with [[Westleigh, Greater Manchester|Westleigh]]; Westhoughton Brook forms the boundary with Daisy Hill; and Red Waters Brook.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=2|ps=none}} The underlying rocks are the [[coal measures]] of the [[Manchester Coalfield]].\n\nAtherton's climate is generally temperate, like the rest of Greater Manchester. The mean highest and lowest temperatures ({{convert|13.2|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}} and {{convert|6.4|\u00b0C|\u00b0F}}) are slightly above the national average, while the annual rainfall ({{convert|806.6|mm|in}}) and average hours of sunshine (1394.5 hours) are respectively above and below the national averages.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/sites/manchester_airport.html |title=Manchester Airport 1971\u20132000 weather averages |publisher=[[Met Office]] |year=2001 |accessdate=9 November 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929103050/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/sites/manchester_airport.html |archivedate=29 September 2007 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |author=Met Office |title=Annual England weather averages |publisher=Met Office |year=2007 |accessdate=9 November 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605024000/http://www.metoffice.gov.uk/climate/uk/averages/19712000/areal/england.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nThe town is situated on the old high road, now the [[A579 road|A579]] from Bolton to Leigh. The [[A577 road|A577]] runs from the town to Tyldesley in one direction and to Wigan in the other.\n{{Geographic Location\n|title     = '''Neighbouring towns, villages, and places'''\n|Northwest = [[Westhoughton]]\n|North     = Over Hulton\n|Northeast = [[Little Hulton]]\n|West      = [[Hindley, Greater Manchester|Hindley]]\n|Centre    = Atherton\n|East      = [[Shakerley]]\n|Southwest = [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]]\n|South     = [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]]\n|Southeast = [[Tyldesley]]\n}}\n\n==Demography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" id=\"toc\" style=\"float: right; margin-left: 1em; width: 40%; font-size: 90%; text-align:center\" cellspacing=\"5\"\n!colspan=\"5\"|'''Atherton Compared'''\n|-\n!width=24% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''[[United Kingdom Census 2001|2001 Census]]'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''Atherton'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''[[Metropolitan Borough of Wigan|Wigan MB]]'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''[[Greater Manchester Urban Area|GM Urban Area]]'''\n!width=19% style=\"font-size:90%;\"|'''England'''\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |Total population||20,302||301,415||2,240,230||49,138,831\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\"|\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |White||98.5%||98.7%||90.3%||90.9%\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |Asian||0.5%||0.4%||6.2%||4.6%\n|-\n|style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" |Black||0.2%||0.2%||1.3%||2.3%\n|-\n!colspan=\"5\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"|Source: Office for National Statistics<ref name=\"2001ethnicdata\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks06--ethnic-group.xls KS06 Ethnic group] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref><ref name=\"2001ethnicdataborough\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211124 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics, Urban area summary results for local authorities|publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-summary-results-for-local-authorities/urban-area-summary-results-for-local-authorities-ks06--ethnic-group.xls KS06 Ethnic group] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n|}\nAt the time of the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]], according to the [[Office for National Statistics]], the Urban Subdivision of Atherton<ref name=\"2001urbanareamap\">{{Citation |url=https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/keystats/sqmap.aspx?kv=1371537476&type=-1&title=D90224+:+Greater+Manchester+Urban+Area+-+Atherton+%28urban+area+subdivisions%29 |title=D90224 : Greater Manchester Urban Area \u2013 Atherton (urban area subdivisions) map|publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=24 September 2009}}</ref> was part of the [[Greater Manchester Urban Area]] and had a total resident population of 20,302, of which 9,908 (48.8%) were male and 10,394 (51.2%) were female,<ref name=KS01 /> living in 8,745&nbsp;households.<ref name=\"2001-KS17\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks17--cars-or-vans.xls KS17 Cars or vans] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>  The settlement occupied {{convert|429|ha|sqmi}}, compared with {{convert|431|ha|sqmi}} in the 1991 census.  Its population density was 47.32&nbsp;people per hectare compared with an average of 40.20 across the Greater Manchester Urban Area.<ref name=KS01 />  The median age of the population was 40, compared with 36 within the Greater Manchester Urban Area and 37 across England and Wales.<ref>{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks02--age-structure.xls KS02 Age structure] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n\nThe majority of the population of Atherton were born in England (96.29%); 1.56% were born elsewhere within the United Kingdom, 0.89% within the rest of the European Union, and 1.26% elsewhere in the world.<ref name=\"2001birthdata\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks05--country-of-birth.xls KS05 Country of birth] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n\nData on religious beliefs across the town in the 2001 census show that 86.6% declared themselves to be [[Christians|Christian]], 7.2% said they held no religion, and 0.3% reported themselves as [[Hindu]].<ref name=\"2001religiondata\">{{Citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks07--religion.xls KS07 Religion] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref>\n\n===Population change===\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%;align:center;width:70%;border:0px;text-align:center;line-height:120%;\"\n! colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|Population growth in Atherton 1777\u20132001\n|-\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Year\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1777\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1801\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1811\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1821\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1831\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1841\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1851\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1861\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1871\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1881\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1891\n|- Align=\"center\"\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Population \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 2,200\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 3,249\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 3,894\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,145\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,181\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,475\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 4,659\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 5,907\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 7,531 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 12,602   \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 15,833  \n|-\n| colspan=\"12\"|\n|-\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Year\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1901\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1911\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1921\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1931\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1939\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1951\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1961\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1971\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1981\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 1991\n! style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color:#000080;\" | 2001\n|-\n! style=\"background: #99CCCC; color: #000080\" height=\"17\" | Population \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 16,211\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 18,982\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 19,856\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 19,989 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 20,098\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 20,596\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 19,756 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | <small>''no data''</small> \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 22,032\n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 21,696 \n| style=\"background: #FFFFFF; color: black;\" | 20,302\n|-\n| colspan=\"12\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:90%;\"|<small>\nParish 1777\u20131861<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.nyt.co.uk/athertonhistory.htm |title=Atherton, Lancashire History |publisher=[[Dave Dutton]] |accessdate=24 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120904163825/http://www.nyt.co.uk/athertonhistory.htm |archivedate=4 September 2012 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{citation |last=Lunn |first=John |title=Atherton Lancashire, A manorial social and industrial history |page=229 |publisher=Atherton UDC |year=1971}}</ref>\n{{\u2022}} Township 1871\u20131891<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TPop&u_id=10297485&c_id=10001043&add=N |title=Atherton Ch/CP |publisher=Vision of Britain |accessdate=24 July 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121026091937/http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_table_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP |archivedate=26 October 2012 }}</ref> {{\u2022}} Urban District 1901\u20131961<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.visionofbritain.org.uk/data_cube_page.jsp?data_theme=T_POP&data_cube=N_TOT_POP&u_id=10003209&c_id=10001043&add=N|title=Atherton UD through time. Population Statistics. Total Population|work=A vision of Britain through time|year=2004|author=Great Britain Historical GIS Project|accessdate=21 September 2009|publisher=University of Portsmouth}}</ref> {{\u2022}} Urban Subdivision 1981\u20132001<ref name=\"KS01\">{{citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=24 July 2008|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks01-usual-resident-population.xls KS01 Usual resident population] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref><ref>{{citation |title=1981 Key Statistics for Urban Areas GB Table 1 |publisher=Office for National Statistics |year=1981}}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/greater_manchester_urban_area.asp |title=Greater Manchester Urban Area 1991 Census |publisher=National Statistics |accessdate=7 December 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090108154641/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/census2001/greater_manchester_urban_area.asp |archivedate=8 January 2009 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref></small>\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Economy==\nThe northern part of Atherton is within the [[Bolton]] [[Travel to Work Area]], whilst the southern part is within the [[Manchester]] TTWA.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.statistics.gov.uk/geography/ttwa.asp |title=Travel to Work Areas |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=24 September 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081001231202/http://www.statistics.gov.uk/geography/ttwa.asp |archivedate=1 October 2008 |url-status = dead|df= }}</ref> The town is within the Manchester [[Larger Urban Zone]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/economic_unit/docs/wp13_towards_a_common_standard.pdf |title=Towards a Common Standard |page=29 |format=PDF |publisher=Greater London Authority |accessdate=5 October 2008 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604094316/http://www.london.gov.uk/archive/mayor/economic_unit/docs/wp13_towards_a_common_standard.pdf |archivedate=4 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAt the time of the 2001 Census, there were 8,755&nbsp;people (43.1%) in employment who were resident in Atherton.  Of these, 19.65% worked in the wholesale and retail trades, including repair of motor vehicles; 19.28% worked within manufacturing industry; and 10.27% worked within the health and social work sector.<ref name=\"2001industrydata\">{{citation |url=http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/publications/re-reference-tables.html?edition=tcm%3A77-211152 |title=Census 2001 Key Statistics \u2013 Urban area results by population size of urban area |publisher=Office for National Statistics |accessdate=16 February 2009|date=22 July 2004|work=ons.gov.uk|at=[http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/census/census-2001-key-statistics/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area/urban-area-results-by-population-size-of-urban-area-ks11a--industry-of-employment---all-people.xls KS11a Industry of employment \u2013 all people] {{XLSlink}}}}</ref> The census recorded the economic activity of residents aged 16\u201374 as 36.7% in full-time employment, 11.0% in part-time employment, 6.8% self-employed, 4.0% unemployed, 1.7% students with jobs, 3.2% students without jobs, 14.6% retired, 6.5% looking after home or family, 11.8% permanently sick or disabled, and 3.8% economically inactive for other reasons. The 4.0% unemployment rate was high compared with the national rate of 3.3%.<ref>{{citation |title=Economic Activity (UV28) |publisher=Office for National Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6114428&c=atherton&d=14&e=9&g=356872&i=1001x1003x1004&o=56&m=0&r=1&s=1257776525837&enc=1&dsFamilyId=107 |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> According to the Office for National Statistics estimates, during the period between April 2001 and March 2002, the average gross income of households was \u00a3380 per week (\u00a319,760 per year), substantially less than the \u00a3470 per week (\u00a324,440) for the rest of the North West.<ref>{{citation |title=Atherton (Ward), Income: Model-Based Estimates |publisher=Office for National Statistics |url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadTableView.do?a=7&b=6114428&c=atherton&d=14&e=4&g=356872&i=1001x1003x1004&o=56&m=0&r=1&s=1257776100512&enc=1&dsFamilyId=266 |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> The average car ownership per household was 1.01, compared with 0.93 across the Greater Manchester Urban Area; 43.74% of households owned a single car or van, and 30.76% owned none.<ref name=\"2001-KS17\" />\n\nAtherton, the third largest retail centre in the Wigan Borough, has a small pedestrian shopping centre. Most shops front on to Market Street and date from late Victorian times, the majority operated by small independent retailers, although there is a supermarket that brings customers into the town centre. Older, low cost, mostly terraced housing, surrounds the centre of town.<ref>{{citation |title=AthertonTownCentreRegeneration, Current position |url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/Services/Environment/BuiltEnvironment/AthertonTownCentreRegeneration.htm |publisher=wigan.gov.uk |accessdate=10 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091119192635/http://www.wigan.gov.uk/Services/Environment/BuiltEnvironment/AthertonTownCentreRegeneration.htm |archivedate=19 November 2009 |url-status = dead|df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bolts and fastenings are still manufactured in Atherton by Smith Bullough, one of a few remaining bolt and nut manufacturers in the UK.<ref name=\"Smith Bullough\">{{citation |url=http://www.smithbullough.com/about_us.html\n|title=Smith Bullough |publisher=smithbullough.com |accessdate=9 November 2009| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20091203042045/http://www.smithbullough.com/about_us.html| archivedate= 3 December 2009 |url-status = live}}</ref>\nAs of 2009, a business park is planned for the former Gibfield Colliery site.<ref>{{citation|title=Showcasing our area |url=http://www.andyburnham.org/showcase.asp |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080310164052/http://www.andyburnham.org/showcase.asp |url-status = dead|archive-date=10 March 2008 |publisher=andyburnham.org |accessdate=10 October 2009 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\n[[File:HoweBridge.jpg|thumb|left|220px|[[Howe Bridge]] [[model village]]. The tall building in the centre is the miners' bath house.]]\nThere are several historic [[Listed buildings in Atherton, Greater Manchester|listed buildings]] in and around Atherton, some, but not all, in the area referred to as Chowbent. They include the 17th-century Alder House,<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068470 |desc=Alder House|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> [[Chowbent Chapel]],<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068472 |desc=Chowbent Unitarian Chapel|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> St John the Baptist's Church (1879),<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068475 |desc=Church of St John the Baptist|access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> and Chanters Farmhouse,<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1309438 |desc=Chanters Farmhouse |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> all of which are [[listed building]]s. The name \"Chanters\" derives from a [[chantry]] granted by the Bishop of Lichfield in 1360 to Sir William de Atherton. The name is also given to a bridge over the Hindsford Brook and a former colliery.{{sfn|Bond|Ackers|Ward|1979|p=22|ps=none}}\n\t\nA pseudo-[[Ancient Egyptian architecture|Egyptian]] [[obelisk]] near the south-east corner of the parish church, similar to one in Leigh, was probably built for Robert Vernon Atherton in 1781. It was restored in 1867 twelve years before the church was finished. It is a Grade II listed structure.<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1309446  |desc=Obelisk adjacent to south-east corner of Church of St. John the Baptist, Market Place |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\nBetween 1873 and 1875, mineowners Fletcher Burrows built a small [[model village]] at Howe Bridge, comprising cottages, shops, a village club, and a bath house for their employees. This Victorian village on either side of Leigh Road,<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1253226 |desc= 94-118, Leigh Road  |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref><ref>{{NHLE |num= 1068474 |desc= 147-191, Leigh Road  |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> together with [[St Michael and All Angels' Church, Howe Bridge|St Michael and All Angel's Church]],<ref>{{NHLE |num= 1268288 |desc= Church of St Michael and All Angels |access-date= 14 December 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref> is a [[conservation area]].<ref>{{citation|title=Howe Bridge Conservation Area |url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/27F6B860-A37C-4A85-A8FD-F2C0E8A60194/0/HoweBridgefirstdraft721kb.pdf |publisher=Wigan MBC |accessdate=16 September 2009 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929210425/http://www.wigan.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/27F6B860-A37C-4A85-A8FD-F2C0E8A60194/0/HoweBridgefirstdraft721kb.pdf |archivedate=29 September 2011 |df= }}</ref> The Ena Mill, one of Atherton's large spinning mills, complete with chimney, survives as a reminder of the textile industry.\n\nAtherton's war memorial is a [[cenotaph]] at the intersection of Leigh Road and Hamilton Street was designed by architect [[Arthur John Hope]] and constructed of [[Darley Dale]] stone. It was unveiled in January 1922 by Private J. Roylance, a soldier blinded in action during the [[First World War]].<ref name=\" Atherton Cenotaph designed by A J Hope \">{{citation\n |title=Atherton Cenotaph designed by A J Hope \n |url=http://www.wigan.gov.uk/News/Archive/October2007/athertoncenotaph.htm \n |publisher=wigan.gov.uk \n |accessdate=4 April 2010 \n |url-status = dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223075737/http://www.wigan.gov.uk/News/Archive/October2007/athertoncenotaph.htm \n |archivedate=23 February 2012 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\nThe Bolton to Leigh road was [[Turnpike trust|turnpiked]] in about 1770 and a toll gate was installed on the Atherton boundary on Bolton Road.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=119|ps=none}} Shakerley Lane toll road emerged near Green Hall on Bolton Road, and was built to get coal from the [[Shakerley]] pits to the turnpike road.\n\nIn 1825, the [[Bolton and Leigh Railway]] received [[Royal Assent]] and the single track railway was opened in 1828 bringing the railway to the western side of the township where it was close to the coal mines at Howe Bridge and Gibfield. Railway stations opened at [[Atherton Bag Lane railway station|Atherton Bag Lane]] and<ref>{{citation |title=Bag Lane Station |url=http://www.subbrit.org.uk/sb-sites/stations/a/atherton/index.shtml |publisher=Subterranea Britannica |accessdate=15 September 2009 }}</ref> further south at [[Atherleigh railway station|Atherleigh]]{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=8|ps=none}} The line was connected to the [[Liverpool and Manchester Railway]] by the Kenyon and Leigh Junction Railway in 1831 and connected to the Tyldesley\u2013Wigan line in 1883 when a station was opened at Chowbent&nbsp;renamed [[Howe Bridge railway station|Howe Bridge]] in 1901.{{sfn|Sweeney|1996|p=8|ps=none}} The [[Lancashire and Yorkshire Railway]]'s line from Manchester to Southport passes to the north of Atherton and [[Atherton railway station|Atherton Station]] which was opened in 1887\u201388 remains open.<ref>{{Cite PastScape |num=499048 |desc=Monument no. 499048 |access-date=17 September 2012 |mode=cs2 |fewer-links=yes}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Atherton railway station in 1989.jpg|thumb|right|220px|[[Atherton railway station]]]]\nIn 1900, a Bill authorising the [[South Lancashire Tramways]] Company to construct over {{convert|62|mi|km}} of tramway in southern Lancashire was given Royal Assent.<ref name=\"Lancashire United\">{{citation |title=History |url=http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |publisher=lancashireunited.org.uk |accessdate=1 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006172556/http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |archive-date=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> \nHowever, by November 1900 the South Lancashire Electric Traction and Power Company had acquired the shares. The first section of tramway opened on 20 October 1902 between [[Lowton]] and Four Lanes Ends via Leigh and Atherton. The company got into financial difficulty and in turn became Lancashire United Tramways later [[Lancashire United Transport]] (LUT). LUT had headquarters and a large depot in Howe Bridge. On 16 December 1933, the last tram ran from Leigh to Four Lane Ends. The following day trolley buses took over.<ref>{{citation |title=LUT |url=http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |publisher=lancashireunited.org.uk |accessdate=31 August 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111006172556/http://www.lancashireunited.org.uk/history.htm |archive-date=6 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nPublic transport in Atherton is co-ordinated by the [[Transport for Greater Manchester]].\nThere are public transport links by rail from Atherton and [[Hag Fold railway station|Hag Fold]] stations to [[Wigan Wallgate railway station|Wigan]] and [[Manchester Victoria railway station|Manchester]] operated by [[Northern (train operating company)|Northern]], and by bus to [[Bolton]], [[Leigh, Greater Manchester|Leigh]], [[Wigan]], Manchester, the [[Trafford Centre]] and [[Middlebrook, Greater Manchester|Middlebrook Retail and Leisure Complex]] operated by [[Diamond Bus North West]] of Atherton, [[Stagecoach Manchester]] and [[First Greater Manchester]].\n\nAtherton is also known for the Vantage V2 bus service by [[First Greater Manchester]].<ref>{{Diff|en:Leigh-Salford-Manchester_Bus_Rapid_Transit|diff=|oldid=917506291|label=en:Leigh-Salford-Manchester_Bus_Rapid_Transit,   oldid 917506291}}{{Circular reference|date=November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\n{{Further|List of schools in Wigan}}\nThe first school in Atherton was Chowbent Grammar School founded before 1654,<ref name=vch/> followed by Chowbent Chapel School in 1734. [[National school (England and Wales)|Lane Top National School]] opened in 1840 and Chowbent Unitarian School and Hindsford St Anne's in 1860. Howe Bridge School opened in 1869 and St Philip's a year later. An undenominational school in Lee Street opened in 1871 followed by St George's and Sacred Heart School in Hindsford in 1873. In the 1890s, the technical school originally opened as a school for science and art, followed by St Richard's in 1891 and Flapper Fold Higher Grade School in 1893. Green Hall Special School opened in 1957, and a new infant school was opened on Lodge Lane for Sacred Heart. Meadowbank Primary School can also be found on Flapper Fold Lane, marking the boundary between Atherton and Hag Fold. Hesketh Fletcher Senior School opened in 1967{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=Appendix 24|ps=none}} and closed on 31 August 2011. [[Atherton Community School]] opened in 2012.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/greater-manchesters-first-free-school-694344 |title=Greater Manchester's first free school opens in Atherton |publisher=[[Manchester Evening News]] |date=3 September 2012 |accessdate=1 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110180101/http://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/greater-manchesters-first-free-school-694344 |archivedate=10 January 2016 |df= }}</ref>\n\n<div style=\"font-size: 95%\">\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n|+List of schools in Atherton \n! School\n! Locality\n! Description\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Ofsted\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Website\n|-\n| Atherton St George's C.E. Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|130300|130300}}\n| [http://www.saintgeorges.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Chowbent Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106443|106443}}\n| [http://www.chowbent.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Hindsford C.E. Primary School\n| Hindsford, Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106441|106441}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20110514154951/http://www.hindsford.wigan.sch.uk/general_info.html website]\n|-\n| Meadowbank Primary and Nursery School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106425|106425}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100523062340/http://www.meadowbank.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Parklee Community School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106426|106426}}\n| [http://www.parklee.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Sacred Heart R.C. Primary School\n| Hindsford, Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106499|106499}}\n| [http://www.athertonsacredheart.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| St Michael's C.E. Primary School, Howe Bridge\n| Howe Bridge, Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106478|106478}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100222021321/http://www.howebridge.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| St Philip's C.E. Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106515|106515}}\n| [http://www.saintphilips.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| St Richard's Catholic Primary School\n| Atherton\n| Primary school\n| {{ofsted|106498|106498}}\n| [http://www.saintrichards.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| Hesketh Fletcher C.E. High School (closed)\n| Atherton\n| Secondary school\n| {{ofsted|106536|106536}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20100411080859/http://www.heskethfletcher.wigan.sch.uk/ website]\n|-\n| New Greenhall School\n| Atherton\n| Special school\n| {{ofsted|131295|131295}}\n| [https://web.archive.org/web/20120307004235/http://www.newgreenhall.wigan.sch.uk/index.htm website]\n|-\n|}\n</div>\n\n==Religion==\n[[File:St John's, Atherton 02.jpg|thumb|left|The tower of [[Church of St John the Baptist, Atherton|Atherton Parish Church]]]]\n{{See also|List of churches in Greater Manchester}}\n\nThree chapels or churches have been built on the site of the Parish [[Church of St John the Baptist, Atherton|Church of St John the Baptist]]. A chapel was built in 1645 by John Atherton. It is sometimes referred to as the Old Bent Chapel.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=37|ps=none}} It remained unconsecrated and was used by the [[Presbyterian]]s.<ref name=vch/> In 1721 Richard Atherton expelled the [[dissenter]]s and the chapel was consecrated in 1723 by the [[Bishop of Sodor and Man]]. A new chapel on the site was consecrated by the [[Bishop of Chester]] in 1814. The present church dedicated to [[John the Baptist|St John the Baptist]] was consecrated in 1879.<ref name=vch/> The church, designed by [[Hubert Austin|Austin]] and [[Edward Graham Paley|Paley]], is built in [[Runcorn]] stone. It is {{convert|60|ft}} wide, {{convert|127|ft}} long, and the {{convert|24|ft|adj=on}} square tower rises to {{convert|120|ft}}. The fabric of the church has suffered from mining [[subsidence]].\n\nThe New Bent or [[Chowbent Chapel]], the earliest [[Nonconformist (Protestantism)|Nonconformist]] chapel in Atherton, was built in 1721 and opened in 1722.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=37|ps=none}} The chapel was built by the Presbyterian congregation after it was expelled from the first chapel.<ref name=vch/>\n\nA mission occupying a barn in Hindsford was replaced in 1901 by [[St Anne's Church, Hindsford|St Anne's Church]] designed by Austin and Paley.<ref name=vch/> It has since been converted to residential use. [[St Michael and All Angels' Church, Howe Bridge|St Michael and All Angels]] at Howe Bridge was built in 1877.<ref name=vch/> There are chapels of the [[Wesleyanism|Wesleyan]], [[Baptist]], Independent [[Methodist]], and Primitive Methodist denominations; a Congregational Church at Howe Bridge was opened in 1904.<ref name=vch/> Roman Catholics celebrated mass in a loft behind the Star and Garter public house on Tyldesley Square until [[Sacred Heart Roman Catholic Church, Hindsford|Sacred Heart Church]] opened in Hindsford in 1869. The site was given by Lord Lilford and building materials were donated by John Holland, manager of [[Yew Tree Colliery]] in Tyldesley. It served the growing Catholic population in Hindsford and Tyldesley.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=180|ps=none}} Sacred Heart closed in 2004, and its parish together with St Richard's in Mayfield Street which opened in 1928, Holy Family in [[Boothstown]], St Ambrose Barlow in [[Astley, Greater Manchester|Astley]], St Gabriel's, Higher Folds in Leigh were united as a single community with [[Margaret Clitherow|St Margaret Clitherow]] as its patron.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.leighpastoralarea.co.uk/index.php/information |title=The Catholic Church in the Leigh Area |publisher=Leigh Pastoral Area |accessdate=28 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213040807/http://www.leighpastoralarea.co.uk/index.php/information |archivedate=13 December 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{citation|url=http://www.sacredheartrchindsford.co.uk/history.html |title=History |publisher=sacredheartrchindsford.co.uk |accessdate=28 April 2013 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130815042815/http://sacredheartrchindsford.co.uk/history.html |archivedate=15 August 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Sport==\nSwimming baths opened in Mayfield Street in 1902 and a swimming club was formed. The baths closed in 2005 and the Atherton & Leigh Amateur Swimming Club moved to the new [[Leigh Sports Village]] facility in 2008.<ref name=\"Atherton Swimming Club FC\">{{citation |url=http://www.athertonsc.org.uk/web/new_web/home_page.htm |title=Atherton Swimming Club |publisher=athertonsc.org.uk |accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nAtherton has two semi-pro football teams, the oldest of which is [[Atherton Collieries A.F.C.]], formed in 1916, who play in the [[Northern Premier League]].<ref name=\"Atherton Collieries FC\">{{citation|url=http://www.pyramidpassion.co.uk/html/atherton_collieries.html|title=Atherton Collieries |publisher=pyramidpassion.co.uk |accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref> \nOthers are [[Atherton Laburnum Rovers F.C.]], members of the North West Counties Football League<ref name=\"Laburnum Rovers FC\">{{citation|url=http://www.athertonlr.co.uk/details.htm|title=AthertonLR|publisher=athertonlr.co.uk|accessdate=28 September 2009|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080522093733/http://www.athertonlr.co.uk/details.htm |archivedate = 22 May 2008}}</ref>\nand Atherton Town FC.<ref name=\"Atherton Town FC\">{{citation |url=http://www.athertontownfc.co.uk/|title=Atherton Town |publisher=athertontownfc.co.uk |accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nAtherton Cricket Club was formed in 1872 and has played in the Bolton and District Cricket Association since 1921.<ref name=\"Atherton Cricket Club\">{{citation|url=http://atherton.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp?|title=Atherton Cricket Club|publisher=atherton.play-cricket.com/|accessdate=2 January 2012|archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130223194247/http://atherton.play-cricket.com/home/home.asp |archivedate=23 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\n==Public services==\nAtherton is policed by the [[Greater Manchester Police]] force from Atherton Police Station, \nwhich covers Atherton, Tyldesley, Astley and Mosley Common, and is one of 5 subdivisions within the Wigan division.<ref name=\"gmp\">{{citation|url=http://www.gmp.police.uk/live/nhoodv3.nsf/index-communities.html?ReadForm&Division=Wigan&Area=Atherton |title=Police Atherton |publisher=Greater Manchester Police |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100808011831/http://www.gmp.police.uk/live/Nhoodv3.nsf/index-communities.html?ReadForm&Division=Wigan&Area=Atherton |archivedate=8 August 2010 |df= }}</ref>\nIt is part of the L division, which covers the entirety of Wigan borough.\nThe statutory emergency fire and rescue service is provided by the [[Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue Service]], \nfrom Atherton  fire station.<ref name=\"fire\">{{citation |url= http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/wigan.aspx|title= Fire and Rescue |publisher= Greater Manchester Fire and Rescue|accessdate=24 May 2010 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080612052419/http://www.manchesterfire.gov.uk/my-area/wigan.aspx |archivedate = 12 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nHealth services in the Wigan borough are provided by the Wigan Borough Clinical Commissioning Group.<ref>{{citation |url=http://www.wiganboroughccg.nhs.uk/|title= Welcome to the Wigan Borough Clinical Commissioning Group Website |publisher= Wigan Borough Clinical Commissioning Group|accessdate=6 November 2013}}</ref> Hospital services are provided by the Wrightington, Wigan and Leigh NHS Foundation Trust who provide an [[Emergency department|Accident and Emergency]] service at Wigan's Royal Albert Edward Infirmary and outpatient clinics at Leigh Infirmary.<ref name=\"W&Lnhs\">{{citation |url= http://www.wiganleigh.nhs.uk/|title= Wigan and Leigh NHS |publisher= Wigan and Leigh NHS|accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nWaste management is co-ordinated by the Wigan Authority, which is a statutory waste disposal authority in its own right.<ref name=\"gmwda\">{{citation |url= http://www.gmwda.gov.uk/|title=Greater Manchester Waste Disposal Authority|publisher= gmwda.gov.uk|accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref>\nAtherton's Distribution Network Operator for electricity is Electricity North West Ltd.<ref name=\"grid\">{{citation |url=  http://www.nationalgrid.com/uk/Electricity/AboutElectricity/DistributionCompanies/|title=Electricity Distribution Companies|publisher=nationalgrid.com/uk|accessdate=24 May 2010}}</ref>\nUnited Utilities manages Atherton's drinking and waste water.<ref name=\"UU\">{{citation|url=http://www.unitedutilities.com/index.htm |title=United Utilities |publisher=United Utilities |accessdate=24 May 2010 |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100102043849/http://unitedutilities.com/index.htm |archivedate=2 January 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Culture==\nAtherton Botanical Garden Club, which is today a social club, was formed in 1850, and organised lectures, study groups and rambles on [[Chat Moss]] for its members.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=176|ps=none}} A public library was opened in 1905 with an [[Andrew Carnegie]] grant.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=199|ps=none}} Bent Chapel already had a library in the Chowbent School, and donated 4,000&nbsp;books to the new town library.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=93|ps=none}} Central Park, a {{convert|10|acre|adj=on}} public park, was created in 1912. Other parks were later provided in Lodge Lane, Hindsford and Devonshire Place. The urban district council also acquired the grounds belonging to Howe Bridge Welfare in 1963.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=200|ps=none}} In the early and mid-20th century Atherton had three cinemas, the Gem in Bullough Street, the Savoy and the Palace on Market Street.{{sfn|Lunn|1971|p=198|ps=none}} An amateur photographic society was formed in 1938.<ref name=\"ADAPS\">{{citation |url=http://www.adaps.org.uk/|title=Atherton & District Amateur Photographic Society |publisher=adaps.org |accessdate=24 September 2009}}</ref> Formby Hall, demolished in 2018, used to host the ''Bent 'n' Bongs'' [[Beer Festival]] over the last weekend of every January.\n\n==Notable residents==\nThere were several ministers of note of [[Chowbent Chapel]] including James Wood, the \"General\" (1672\u20131759), who distinguished himself at the [[Battle of Preston (1715)|Battle of Preston]] in 1715.{{sfn|Wright|1921|p=23|ps=none}} [[Thomas Walker Horsfield]]<ref>{{citation |title=Thomas Walker Horsfield |url=http://theweald.org/N10.asp?Nid=2181 |publisher=The Weald.org |accessdate=20 September 2009 }}</ref> (1792\u20131837) was a historian and topographer. [[Joseph Nightingale]] (1775\u20131824), born in Chowbent, was a prolific English writer and [[preacher]] who subsequently became a Unitarian.\n[[Eric Laithwaite]] (1921\u20131997) was an engineer, principally known for his development of the [[linear induction motor]] and [[Maglev]] rail system.<ref>{{citation |title= Obituary \u2013 Professor Eric Laithwaite |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/publications/reporterarchive/0055/feat03.htm  |publisher=Imperial College |accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> Chess grandmaster [[Nigel Short]] grew up in Atherton and attended St Philip's School.<ref>{{citation |title= Nigel Short |url=http://www.chessbase.com/newsdetail.asp?newsid=2426 |publisher=chessbase.com|accessdate=9 November 2009}}</ref> Architect [[Arthur John Hope]] (1875\u20131960), a partner in [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] was born and lived in Atherton.<ref name=\" Atherton Cenotaph designed by A J Hope \"/> [[Edward Ormerod]], mining engineer at Gib Field Colliery, invented the Ormerod detaching hook, an important mining safety device.<ref>{{citation | url=http://www.edwardormerodandco.co.uk/history.html|title= Edward Ormerod and Co Ltd|accessdate =27 February 2011}}</ref>\n\nAndy Whyment, Coronation Street actor (Kirk Sutherland) and runner up of I'm a celebrity 2019\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Greater Manchester}}\n*[[Listed buildings in Atherton, Greater Manchester]]\n*[[List of people from Wigan]]\n*[[List of mills in Wigan]]\n*[[List of mining disasters in Lancashire]]\n\n==References==\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{citation |last1=Bond |first1= |last2=Ackers |first2= |last3=Ward |first3= |title=Leigh Homesteads |publisher=Leigh Local History Society Publication No7 |year=1979}}\n*{{citation |last=Holcroft |first=Fred |title=Silk Manufacturing in Leigh |publisher=Leigh Local History Society Publication No21 |year=1998}}\n*{{citation |last=Lunn |first=John |title=Atherton Lancashire, A manorial social and industrial history |publisher=Atherton UDC |year=1971}}\n*{{citation |last=Mills |first=A. D. |title=Dictionary of English Place-Names |publisher=Oxford |year=1998 |isbn=0-19-280074-4 |url=http://www.oxfordreference.com/views/ENTRY.html?entry=t40.e651&srn=1&ssid=931364015#FIRSTHIT}} {{Subscription}} \n*{{citation |last1=Pollard |first1=Richard |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |last3=Sharples |first3=Joseph |title=Lancashire: Liverpool and the South West |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-10910-8}}}\n*{{citation |last=Sweeney |first=D. J. |title=A Lancashire Triangle Part One |publisher=Triangle Publishing |year=1996 |isbn=0-9529333-0-6}}\n*{{citation |last=Sweeney |first=D. J. |title=A Lancashire Triangle Part Two |publisher=Triangle Publishing |year=1997 |isbn=0-9529333-2-2}}\n*{{citation |last=Wright |first=J. J. |title=The Story of Chowbent Chapel |publisher=Chowbent Chapel |year=1921}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Atherton, Greater Manchester}}\n*[http://www.lan-opc.org.uk/Atherton/index.html  Atherton at lan-opc]\n* {{Genuki|county=LAN|Atherton}}\n*[http://www.mortfamily.net/ Mort family, Alder House]\n{{Greater Manchester}}\n{{Good article}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Atherton, Greater Manchester| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Greater Manchester]]\n[[Category:Geography of the Metropolitan Borough of Wigan]]\n", "name_user": "I dream of horses", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:James Grundy\u2192James Grundy (politician)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atherton,_Greater_Manchester"}
{"title_page": "J\u00falia Szendrey", "text_new": "{{eastern name order|Szendrey J\u00falia}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = J\u00falia Szendrey\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Pet\u0151fi S\u00e1ndorn\u00e9.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=y|1828|12|29}}<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite web|url=https://mnl.gov.hu/mnl/ol/hirek/szabadsag_es_szerelem|title=Szabads\u00e1g \u00e9s szerelem|publisher=[[National Archives of Hungary]]|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Keszthely]], [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Kingdom of Hungary]]<ref name=\"gov\" />\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1868|09|06|1828|12|29}} \n| death_place      = [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]], [[Austria-Hungary]]<ref name=\"szinnyei\">{{cite book|url=https://mek.oszk.hu/03600/03630/html/p/p19749.htm|chapter=Pet\u0151fi S\u00e1ndorn\u00e9|title=Magyar \u00edr\u00f3k \u00e9lete \u00e9s munk\u00e1i|author=Szinnyei J\u00f3zsef|year=1891|publisher=Magyar Elektronikus K\u00f6nyvt\u00e1r|language=hu}}</ref>\n| resting_place    = [[Kerepesi Cemetery]]\n| occupation       = writer, translator, poet\n| language         = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = Hungarian\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi]]|1847|1849}}<br>{{marriage|[[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t (historian)|\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t]]|1850|1868}}\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = 5\n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''J\u00falia Szendrey''' (29 December 1828 \u2013 6 September 1868) was a Hungarian poet, writer and translator, most known as the wife of celebrated Hungarian poet [[S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi]].<ref name=\"Rubicon\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.rubicon.hu/magyar/oldalak/1868_szeptember_6_szendrey_julia_halala/|title=Szendrey J\u00falia hal\u00e1la|journal=Rubicon|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu}}</ref>\n\n== Life and works ==\n[[File:Szendrey J\u00falia Kisk\u0151r\u00f6s Domonkos.JPG|thumb|Szendrey's statue in [[Kisk\u0151r\u00f6s]]]]\nJ\u00falia Szendrey was born in \u00dajmajor, [[Keszthely]], her father was Ign\u00e1c Szendrey (1800\u20131895), a farm overseer for various noble families during his career, including the [[Festetics family]] and the [[K\u00e1rolyi]] family.<ref name=\"szendreyign\u00e1c\">{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:S3HT-XKP9-8H1?i=940&wc=M6WL-MNL%3A101522301%2C107388201&cc=1542666|title= Szendrey Ign\u00e1c gy\u00e1szjelent\u00e9se|publisher=familysearch.org|language=hu|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"Rubicon\" /> Her mother was Anna G\u00e1lovics.<ref name=\"gov\" /> She spent four years studying in [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] at an institute for daughters of affluent families.<ref name=\"szinnyei\" /> She was fluent in foreign languages, played the piano and liked dancing, however, she was not fond of parties and showing her skills to others. She was happiest reading poems and books, of [[Heinrich Heine]], [[George Sand]] and the like.<ref name=\"szinnyei\" />\n\nAs she was an educated lady, fond of literature and poetry, she immediately fell in love with [[S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi]], when they met in [[Nagyk\u00e1roly]] in 1846. Despite opposition from her family, the couple got married a year later in [[Erd\u0151d]]. As the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848]] broke out, Pet\u0151fi also joined the army, and moved his family to [[Debrecen]]. Their son, [[Zolt\u00e1n Pet\u0151fi|Zolt\u00e1n]] was born on 15 December 1848.<ref name=\"gov\" />\n\nWhen Pet\u0151fi disappeared during the war, and then was reported dead, Szendrey was incapable of accepting it. She traveled to [[Transylvania]] to look for him, and also applied for a passport to Turkey, should her husband be there. As she was denied traveling abroad, in despair, she turned to a trustworthy friend, historian [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t (historian)|\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t]].<ref name=\"szinnyei\" /><ref name=\"Rubicon\" /> They got married in 1850, which was then frowned upon and for decades, Szendrey was stigmatized for her decision to remarry, and also for various rumours surrounding her behaviour, fuelled by writings and poems of well-known literary figures like [[J\u00e1nos Arany]]. She possibly married him looking for protection.<ref name=\"hetek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hetek.hu/arcok/201703/julia_az_elatkozott_ozvegy_petofi_ozvegyendiek_igazi_arca|title=J\u00falia, az el\u00e1tkozott \u00f6zvegy - Pet\u0151fi \u00f6zvegy\u00e9nek igazi arca|date=2017-03-10|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu|publisher=Hetek}}</ref> Decades after her death, her long lost diary was recovered and partially published, dispelling previous accusations.<ref name=\"hetek\" />\n\nSzendrey bore four children for Horv\u00e1t, while her relationship with her first-born son Zolt\u00e1n deteriorated, as the young man was increasingly living his life like his father, Pet\u0151fi did. He eventually died very young in [[tuberculosis]], in 1870.<ref name=\"gov\" /> In the 1950s, Szendrey wrote several poems, a diary and she translated several of [[Hans Christian Andersen]]'s tales.<ref name=\"Rubicon\" />\n\nHer second marriage also ended in tragedy. She was diagnosed with [[cervical cancer]], and suddenly in 1867 she decided to separate from her husband and moved to a small apartment in Pest, financed by her father. In her diary, she wrote that her second husband was not loyal to her, and he forced her to do her \"conjugal duty\" even after a doctor warned him that she was sick.<ref name=\"hetek\" /> She died in that small apartment in 1868, on her deathbed she dictated a letter to her father that read, \"Father said I would be unhappy with S\u00e1ndor. A woman has not yet experienced such happiness that I felt when I was together with my S\u00e1ndor. I was his queen, he adored me and I adored him. We were the happiest couple in the world, and had fate not intervened, we would still be so.\"<ref name=\"gov\" />\n\nAfter reading her letter, where she confessed of the wrongdoings of her husband, her father did not allow Horv\u00e1t to bury her, he himself arranged the funeral.<ref name=\"hetek\" /> 60 years after Pet\u0151fi's death, she was laid to rest with the rest of the Pet\u0151fi family members in [[Kerepesi Cemetery]], the inscription on the tomb includes her birth name and identifies her as S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi's wife, even though she died as \u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t's spouse.<ref name=\"Rubicon\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irodalomismeret.hu/files/2014_2/galyas_cintia.pdf|title=Szendrey J\u00falia mint k\u00f6lt\u0151, m\u0171ford\u00edt\u00f3, m\u00fazsa \u00e9s n\u0151|publisher=Irodalomismeret|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060524090516/http://www.agt.bme.hu/staff_h/varga/foto/kerepesi/petofi.html|url=http://www.agt.bme.hu/staff_h/varga/foto/kerepesi/petofi.html|archivedate=2006-05-24|title=Pet\u0151fi csal\u00e1d|language=hu|publisher=Dr. Varga J\u00f3zsef}}</ref>\n\n== Memorials ==\nThere are several statues of J\u00falia Szendrey in Hungary, for example in [[Kisk\u0151r\u00f6s]] and in [[Mez\u0151ber\u00e9ny]]. In 2018, her statue was erected in [[Copenhagen]] at the Hungarian embassy building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sonline.hu/kultura/hazai-kultura/szobrot-kapott-koppenhagaban-szendrey-julia-1330270/|title=Szobrot kapott Koppenh\u00e1g\u00e1ban Szendrey J\u00falia|publisher=Sonline|date=2018-12-07|accessdate=2019-01-09|language=hu}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n* [https://xorxor.hu/projects/museum/szendrey.html Poems of J\u00falia Szendrey, 2019, Pet\u0151fi Literary Museum]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Szendrey, Julia}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:Hungarian women poets]]\n[[Category:Hungarian translators]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Keszthely]]\n[[Category:19th-century Hungarian poets]]\n[[Category:19th-century Hungarian women writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{eastern name order|Szendrey J\u00falia}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| embed            = \n| honorific_prefix = \n| name             = J\u00falia Szendrey\n| honorific_suffix = \n| image            = Pet\u0151fi S\u00e1ndorn\u00e9.jpg\n| image_size       = \n| image_upright    = \n| alt              = \n| caption          = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| pseudonym        = \n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date|df=y|1828|12|29}}<ref name=\"gov\">{{cite web|url=https://mnl.gov.hu/mnl/ol/hirek/szabadsag_es_szerelem|title=Szabads\u00e1g \u00e9s szerelem|publisher=[[National Archives of Hungary]]|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu}}</ref>\n| birth_place      = [[Keszthely]], [[Kingdom of Hungary (1526\u20131867)|Kingdom of Hungary]]<ref name=\"gov\" />\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|1868|09|06|1828|12|29}} \n| death_place      = [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]], [[Austria-Hungary]]<ref name=\"szinnyei\">{{cite book|url=https://mek.oszk.hu/03600/03630/html/p/p19749.htm|chapter=Pet\u0151fi S\u00e1ndorn\u00e9|title=Magyar \u00edr\u00f3k \u00e9lete \u00e9s munk\u00e1i|author=Szinnyei J\u00f3zsef|year=1891|publisher=Magyar Elektronikus K\u00f6nyvt\u00e1r|language=hu}}</ref>\n| resting_place    = [[Kerepesi Cemetery]]\n| occupation       = writer, translator, poet\n| language         = [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]]\n| residence        = \n| nationality      = Hungarian\n| citizenship      = \n| education        = \n| alma_mater       = \n| home_town        = \n| period           = \n| genre            = <!-- or: | genres = -->\n| subject          = <!-- or: | subjects = -->\n| movement         = \n| notableworks     = <!-- or: | notablework = -->\n| spouse           = {{marriage|[[S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi]]|1847|1849}}<br>{{marriage|[[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t (historian)|\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t]]|1850|1868}}\n| partner          = <!-- or: | partners = -->\n| children         = 5\n| relatives        = \n| awards           = \n| signature        = \n| signature_alt    = \n| years_active     = \n| module           = \n| website          = <!-- {{URL|example.org}} -->\n| portaldisp       = <!-- \"on\", \"yes\", \"true\", etc.; or omit -->\n}}\n'''J\u00falia Szendrey''' (29 December 1828 \u2013 6 September 1868) was a Hungarian poet, writer and translator, most known as the wife of celebrated Hungarian poet [[S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi]].<ref name=\"Rubicon\">{{cite journal|url=http://www.rubicon.hu/magyar/oldalak/1868_szeptember_6_szendrey_julia_halala/|title=Szendrey J\u00falia hal\u00e1la|journal=Rubicon|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu}}</ref>\n\n== Life and works ==\n[[File:Szendrey J\u00falia Kisk\u0151r\u00f6s Domonkos.JPG|thumb|Szendrey's statue in [[Kisk\u0151r\u00f6s]]]]\nJ\u00falia Szendrey was born in \u00dajmajor, [[Keszthely]], her father was Ign\u00e1c Szendrey (1800\u20131895), a farm overseer for various noble families during his career, including the [[Festetics family]] and the [[K\u00e1rolyi]] family.<ref name=\"szendreyign\u00e1c\">{{Cite web|url=https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/3:1:S3HT-XKP9-8H1?i=940&wc=M6WL-MNL%3A101522301%2C107388201&cc=1542666|title= Szendrey Ign\u00e1c gy\u00e1szjelent\u00e9se|publisher=familysearch.org|language=hu|accessdate=2020-03-21}}</ref><ref name=\"gov\" /><ref name=\"Rubicon\" /> Her mother was Anna G\u00e1lovics.<ref name=\"gov\" /> She spent four years studying in [[Pest, Hungary|Pest]] at an institute for daughters of affluent families.<ref name=\"szinnyei\" /> She was fluent in foreign languages, played the piano and liked dancing, however, she was not fond of parties and showing her skills to others. She was happiest reading poems and books, of [[Heinrich Heine]], [[George Sand]] and the like.<ref name=\"szinnyei\" />\n\nAs she was an educated lady, fond of literature and poetry, she immediately fell in love with [[S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi]], when they met in [[Nagyk\u00e1roly]] in 1846. Despite opposition from her family, the couple got married a year later in [[Erd\u0151d]]. As the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1848]] broke out, Pet\u0151fi also joined the army, and moved his family to [[Debrecen]]. Their son, [[Zolt\u00e1n Pet\u0151fi|Zolt\u00e1n]] was born on 15 December, 1848.<ref name=\"gov\" />\n\nWhen Pet\u0151fi disappeared during the war, and then was reported dead, Szendrey was incapable of accepting it. She traveled to [[Transylvania]] to look for him, and also applied for a passport to Turkey, should her husband be there. As she was denied traveling abroad, in despair, she turned to a trustworthy friend, historian [[\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t (historian)|\u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t]].<ref name=\"szinnyei\" /><ref name=\"Rubicon\" /> They got married in 1850, which was then frowned upon and for decades, Szendrey was stigmatized for her decision to remarry, and also for various rumours surrounding her behaviour, fuelled by writings and poems of well-known literary figures like [[J\u00e1nos Arany]]. She possibly married him looking for protection.<ref name=\"hetek\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hetek.hu/arcok/201703/julia_az_elatkozott_ozvegy_petofi_ozvegyendiek_igazi_arca|title=J\u00falia, az el\u00e1tkozott \u00f6zvegy - Pet\u0151fi \u00f6zvegy\u00e9nek igazi arca|date=2017-03-10|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu|publisher=Hetek}}</ref> Decades after her death, her long lost diary was recovered and partially published, dispelling previous accusations.<ref name=\"hetek\" />\n\nSzendrey bore four children for Horv\u00e1t, while her relationship with her first-born son Zolt\u00e1n deteriorated, as the young man was increasingly living his life like his father, Pet\u0151fi did. He eventually died very young in [[tuberculosis]], in 1870.<ref name=\"gov\" /> In the 1950s, Szendrey wrote several poems, a diary and she translated several of [[Hans Christian Andersen]]'s tales.<ref name=\"Rubicon\" /> \n\nHer second marriage also ended in tragedy. She was diagnosed with [[cervical cancer]], and suddenly in 1867 she decided to separate from her husband and moved to a small apartment in Pest, financed by her father. In her diary, she wrote that her second husband was not loyal to her, and he forced her to do her \"conjugal duty\" even after a doctor warned him that she was sick.<ref name=\"hetek\" /> She died in that small apartment in 1868, on her deathbed she dictated a letter to her father that read, \"Father said I would be unhappy with S\u00e1ndor. A woman has not yet experienced such happiness that I felt when I was together with my S\u00e1ndor. I was his queen, he adored me and I adored him. We were the happiest couple in the world, and had fate not intervened, we would still be so.\"<ref name=\"gov\" />\n\nAfter reading her letter, where she confessed of the wrongdoings of her husband, her father did not allow Horv\u00e1t to bury her, he himself arranged the funeral.<ref name=\"hetek\" /> 60 years after Pet\u0151fi's death, she was laid to rest with the rest of the Pet\u0151fi family members in [[Kerepesi Cemetery]], the inscription on the tomb includes her birth name and identifies her as S\u00e1ndor Pet\u0151fi's wife, even though she died as \u00c1rp\u00e1d Horv\u00e1t's spouse.<ref name=\"Rubicon\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irodalomismeret.hu/files/2014_2/galyas_cintia.pdf|title=Szendrey J\u00falia mint k\u00f6lt\u0151, m\u0171ford\u00edt\u00f3, m\u00fazsa \u00e9s n\u0151|publisher=Irodalomismeret|accessdate=2020-03-21|language=hu}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060524090516/http://www.agt.bme.hu/staff_h/varga/foto/kerepesi/petofi.html|url=http://www.agt.bme.hu/staff_h/varga/foto/kerepesi/petofi.html|archivedate=2006-05-24|title=Pet\u0151fi csal\u00e1d|language=hu|publisher=Dr. Varga J\u00f3zsef}}</ref>\n\n== Memorials ==\nThere are several statues of J\u00falia Szendrey in Hungary, for example in [[Kisk\u0151r\u00f6s]] and in [[Mez\u0151ber\u00e9ny]]. In 2018, her statue was erected in [[Copenhagen]] at the Hungarian embassy building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sonline.hu/kultura/hazai-kultura/szobrot-kapott-koppenhagaban-szendrey-julia-1330270/|title=Szobrot kapott Koppenh\u00e1g\u00e1ban Szendrey J\u00falia|publisher=Sonline|date=2018-12-07|accessdate=2019-01-09|language=hu}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commonscat}}\n* [https://xorxor.hu/projects/museum/szendrey.html Poems of J\u00falia Szendrey, 2019, Pet\u0151fi Literary Museum]\n\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1828 births]]\n[[Category:Hungarian women poets]]\n[[Category:Hungarian women writers]]\n[[Category:Hungarian translators]]\n[[Category:1868 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Keszthely]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "duplicate categorization; already in subcat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C3%BAlia_Szendrey"}
